WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.220 --> 00:00:05.200
Ladies and gentlemen, our program is about to begin.

2
00:00:08.760 --> 00:00:12.560
The AACR Annual Meeting is the focal point of the cancer research

3
00:00:12.620 --> 00:00:16.310
community, where attendees gather to share the latest advances in

4
00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:17.820
cancer science and medicine.

5
00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:20.920
With the theme of Precision. Partnership.

6
00:00:21.220 --> 00:00:24.920
Purpose.: Advancing Cancer Science to Save Lives Globally,

7
00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:29.210
the AACR Annual Meeting highlights the work of the best minds in

8
00:00:29.260 --> 00:00:31.320
cancer research from around the world.

9
00:00:32.180 --> 00:00:33.560
Welcome to San Diego.

10
00:00:41.220 --> 00:00:41.800
Good morning.

11
00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:47.380
I'm Andrew Chan, and I'm a gastroenterologist and epidemiologist at

12
00:00:47.420 --> 00:00:48.960
Massachusetts General Hospital.

13
00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:53.320
It's my honor this morning to chair this special plenary

14
00:00:53.330 --> 00:00:55.880
session on early-onset cancers.

15
00:00:58.220 --> 00:00:59.440
These are my disclosures.

16
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.760
So the topic of early-onset cancers has really captured the

17
00:01:06.820 --> 00:01:10.610
attention of the cancer research community, our patients, and their

18
00:01:10.640 --> 00:01:11.220
families.

19
00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:15.220
In addition, it has also captured the attention of the public.

20
00:01:16.220 --> 00:01:19.640
This slide illustrates just a few of the headlines that have been

21
00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:23.660
generated in one newspaper in the last year around the topic

22
00:01:23.700 --> 00:01:24.980
of early-onset cancers.

23
00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:30.040
Underlying these headlines is substantial population surveillance

24
00:01:30.100 --> 00:01:33.680
data, which has demonstrated these rising trends of early-onset

25
00:01:33.740 --> 00:01:37.560
cancer that are so alarming. And we're fortunate this morning to have as

26
00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:41.500
our first speaker, Dr. Hyuna Sung of the American Cancer Society, who will

27
00:01:41.560 --> 00:01:42.480
cover this topic.

28
00:01:44.920 --> 00:01:48.680
In addition, when we think about early-onset cancer, we also need to think about

29
00:01:48.980 --> 00:01:52.780
etiology. And the question is: why are we seeing such a rise in

30
00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:56.710
early-onset cancer? This also obviously has captured the attention

31
00:01:56.760 --> 00:02:00.620
of the public with an idea that understanding the why will help

32
00:02:00.660 --> 00:02:04.500
us understand how to prevent these cancers in the future.

33
00:02:04.510 --> 00:02:05.250
And so with that,

34
00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:10.000
in my talk, I will focus on the emerging epidemiology around

35
00:02:10.060 --> 00:02:13.800
colorectal cancer and how colorectal cancer is a

36
00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:17.820
potential exemplar cancer for how we can study early-onset

37
00:02:17.880 --> 00:02:19.980
cancer to lead to preventive interventions.

38
00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:22.940
That will then be followed by a talk by Dr.

39
00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:26.900
Ludmil Alexandrov, who will present some provocative data on the

40
00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:30.300
potential role of the microbiome on early-onset cancers.

41
00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:33.870
And then finally, this will be followed by Dr.

42
00:02:34.120 --> 00:02:38.040
Pepper Shedden of Oregon Health &amp; Sciences University, who will speak about

43
00:02:38.060 --> 00:02:39.520
early-onset breast cancer.

44
00:02:41.020 --> 00:02:44.100
So with that, it's my pleasure to present our first speaker,

45
00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:48.010
who's Dr. Hyuna Sung. She's a senior principal

46
00:02:48.120 --> 00:02:51.890
scientist at the American Cancer Society, and she's been a

47
00:02:51.980 --> 00:02:55.920
leader in the field of population surveillance data, and she will cover these

48
00:02:55.960 --> 00:02:59.920
really alarming trends across different cancer types. Welcome, Dr.

49
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:00.280
Sung.

50
00:03:11.730 --> 00:03:12.700
Good morning, everyone.

51
00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:17.150
It's truly an honor and privilege to speak here as a cancer

52
00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:20.140
surveillance researcher. For me, this

53
00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:24.120
invitation reflects the urgency we share in

54
00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:26.540
understanding cancer trends

55
00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:28.420
among young adults.

56
00:03:29.460 --> 00:03:30.260
Before I begin,

57
00:03:31.140 --> 00:03:34.880
I'd like to let you know that my talk will sound quite different

58
00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:37.240
from the plenaries you've heard so far.

59
00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:42.070
I will take us on a retrospective view, but by the end of the

60
00:03:42.180 --> 00:03:42.560
talk,

61
00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:46.820
I hope to leave you a prospective perspective as well.

62
00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:53.260
I think we all agree on this.

63
00:03:54.620 --> 00:03:58.160
Cancer incidence rates are rising among young adults across

64
00:03:58.300 --> 00:04:00.540
multiple cancer types in many countries.

65
00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:05.400
But beyond that, there is much less agreement on

66
00:04:05.460 --> 00:04:09.040
what these trends signify and whether we should be

67
00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:09.720
concerned.

68
00:04:10.700 --> 00:04:14.340
Early-onset colorectal cancer is a clear exception, where the

69
00:04:14.380 --> 00:04:17.780
evidence is strong and then the significance is

70
00:04:17.860 --> 00:04:19.240
widely recognized.

71
00:04:20.579 --> 00:04:24.200
But for other cancers, the increases are often

72
00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:26.360
questioned, mainly for two reasons.

73
00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:27.480
First,

74
00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:32.280
even with a rapid increase, the absolute rates remain

75
00:04:32.340 --> 00:04:34.460
low, raising concerns

76
00:04:35.460 --> 00:04:39.200
that focusing on young onset cancer may divert the much

77
00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:43.040
needed attention from cancers among older

78
00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:47.020
adults. And second, the trends are largely

79
00:04:47.180 --> 00:04:50.980
driven by the increased detection, not by a

80
00:04:51.060 --> 00:04:52.980
true increase in the risk.

81
00:04:54.300 --> 00:04:58.140
So today, rather than dismissing these trends or

82
00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:01.480
oversimplifying them, I'd like to offer a

83
00:05:01.520 --> 00:05:04.890
perspective that may help us better assess these

84
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.580
trends and start to disentangle the

85
00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:11.620
complex drivers behind them.

86
00:05:13.260 --> 00:05:16.680
Let me start with the burden. Every day, over

87
00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:20.800
9,000 people under age 50 diagnosed with cancer

88
00:05:20.840 --> 00:05:21.520
worldwide,

89
00:05:22.740 --> 00:05:25.420
and over 3,000 die from the disease.

90
00:05:27.700 --> 00:05:31.520
And yet, the burden of the disease among young adults

91
00:05:31.640 --> 00:05:32.440
remains small,

92
00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:37.380
about one in five cases and one in ten deaths.

93
00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:43.880
And this obviously reflects the strong age gradient

94
00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:44.860
in cancer risk.

95
00:05:46.420 --> 00:05:50.260
And yes, the risk is very low in young people in general.

96
00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:52.540
However,

97
00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:57.360
cancer trends in young adults has long been a key

98
00:05:57.420 --> 00:05:59.040
focus in cancer surveillance

99
00:05:59.140 --> 00:06:03.152
researchBecause

100
00:06:03.162 --> 00:06:05.272
they serve as early signals.

101
00:06:07.732 --> 00:06:08.552
As they age,

102
00:06:09.392 --> 00:06:13.152
they carry their risk forward to the future, and

103
00:06:13.192 --> 00:06:16.772
by doing so, they shape and drive the future cancer

104
00:06:16.812 --> 00:06:17.272
burden.

105
00:06:22.472 --> 00:06:26.272
And here's an irony. To better assess cancer trends among young

106
00:06:26.312 --> 00:06:29.932
adults, we may want to set aside age for the moment,

107
00:06:30.332 --> 00:06:32.892
because age is a moving target.

108
00:06:34.252 --> 00:06:37.372
Ask whether cancer rate is rising at age 45 in

109
00:06:37.412 --> 00:06:40.612
1995 versus age 45 in

110
00:06:40.872 --> 00:06:41.812
2025.

111
00:06:43.372 --> 00:06:47.112
We are talking about entirely different generations who

112
00:06:47.152 --> 00:06:48.662
grew up in different worlds

113
00:06:49.672 --> 00:06:53.352
in terms of social norms, environment, technologies,

114
00:06:53.672 --> 00:06:56.592
lifestyle, medical system, and so on.

115
00:06:57.252 --> 00:07:00.932
And that's where birth cohort framework becomes powerful.

116
00:07:02.072 --> 00:07:02.611
Instead of

117
00:07:02.712 --> 00:07:06.502
following

118
00:07:06.532 --> 00:07:09.992
people by age or calendar period, we follow

119
00:07:10.002 --> 00:07:11.652
generations by birth year.

120
00:07:14.412 --> 00:07:16.942
And that changes our question entirely.

121
00:07:17.752 --> 00:07:21.712
Instead of asking whether cancer rates are rising among young adults,

122
00:07:22.232 --> 00:07:22.792
we ask

123
00:07:24.232 --> 00:07:27.932
whether today's young generation face a higher

124
00:07:28.092 --> 00:07:31.772
cancer risk as they age, compared with their parent

125
00:07:31.912 --> 00:07:32.542
generation.

126
00:07:35.452 --> 00:07:39.272
A birth cohort framework allows us to capture cancer

127
00:07:39.332 --> 00:07:43.172
risk across a lifetime, reflecting exposures

128
00:07:43.292 --> 00:07:43.472
that

129
00:07:44.312 --> 00:07:47.752
begin early in life and accumulate over time.

130
00:07:48.792 --> 00:07:50.972
And this is particularly relevant

131
00:07:51.892 --> 00:07:55.572
to young onset cancer or early onset cancers, where

132
00:07:55.592 --> 00:07:56.962
latency may be shorter,

133
00:07:58.312 --> 00:08:02.232
and then early life exposures may play a disproportionately

134
00:08:02.292 --> 00:08:02.972
larger role.

135
00:08:04.092 --> 00:08:07.952
And by setting aside age, we can more fairly compare the

136
00:08:07.992 --> 00:08:09.472
risk across generations,

137
00:08:10.272 --> 00:08:13.952
and we can even construct the whole trajectory of cancer risk

138
00:08:13.992 --> 00:08:17.431
across generations, spanning decades, even a century.

139
00:08:19.272 --> 00:08:20.512
And this is how we do it.

140
00:08:21.332 --> 00:08:24.612
For each generation, we estimate cancer

141
00:08:24.692 --> 00:08:27.992
rates across life course from the

142
00:08:28.052 --> 00:08:32.021
youth to old age and distill this into a single

143
00:08:32.112 --> 00:08:34.793
measure and compare them across generations.

144
00:08:37.533 --> 00:08:39.653
But data are incomplete,

145
00:08:41.012 --> 00:08:44.812
because we don't observe the full data for all

146
00:08:45.772 --> 00:08:48.712
life course for each birth cohort.

147
00:08:49.332 --> 00:08:51.692
So we need to rely on modeling.

148
00:08:53.352 --> 00:08:56.952
The age-period cohort modeling fills in those gap

149
00:08:57.772 --> 00:09:01.252
while accounting for the differences in age across

150
00:09:01.312 --> 00:09:04.592
generations and also period influences.

151
00:09:05.512 --> 00:09:09.172
By period influences, I refer to short-term and

152
00:09:09.252 --> 00:09:12.722
abrupt changes in cancer incidence rates,

153
00:09:13.292 --> 00:09:14.732
most often caused by

154
00:09:15.552 --> 00:09:18.452
changes in detection and diagnostic practices.

155
00:09:20.312 --> 00:09:24.272
In the following slides, I will present result that applied

156
00:09:24.312 --> 00:09:27.912
this APC framework to the US National Cancer

157
00:09:27.972 --> 00:09:28.792
Registry data,

158
00:09:30.212 --> 00:09:33.932
along with selected international comparisons based on

159
00:09:33.972 --> 00:09:37.832
CI5+ data compiled by International Agency

160
00:09:37.892 --> 00:09:39.012
for Research on Cancer.

161
00:09:41.032 --> 00:09:42.732
Let me start with the cancers

162
00:09:44.152 --> 00:09:47.692
where incidence rates are higher among younger generations.

163
00:09:48.712 --> 00:09:52.592
This slide shows 17 cancer types for which

164
00:09:53.052 --> 00:09:56.912
people born in 1990 have higher rates compared

165
00:09:56.972 --> 00:09:59.252
with those born in 1955.

166
00:10:00.212 --> 00:10:03.672
The largest increase is seen for small intestinal cancer,

167
00:10:04.352 --> 00:10:07.292
followed by thyroid, kidney, pancreatic cancers.

168
00:10:07.752 --> 00:10:11.192
In the next tier, about twofold difference for breast,

169
00:10:11.652 --> 00:10:14.832
female liver, uterine cancer, followed by

170
00:10:15.532 --> 00:10:19.371
multiple GI cancers, including colorectal, and testicular

171
00:10:19.431 --> 00:10:20.332
cancer at the end.

172
00:10:22.532 --> 00:10:26.052
But this is just a partial view. Each cancer type

173
00:10:26.092 --> 00:10:28.992
deserves a closer look, but I want to

174
00:10:29.832 --> 00:10:33.712
focus a few cancer types to illustrate key birth cohort patterns.

175
00:10:35.972 --> 00:10:37.812
Starting with colorectal cancer.

176
00:10:39.012 --> 00:10:42.732
Cohort rate ratio is one of the most widely

177
00:10:42.812 --> 00:10:46.392
used parameter that characterize birth cohort patterns.

178
00:10:47.232 --> 00:10:47.932
It measures

179
00:10:48.912 --> 00:10:52.592
relative difference in cancer risk across

180
00:10:52.652 --> 00:10:56.222
birth years, using the midyear birth cohort as the

181
00:10:56.272 --> 00:10:56.872
reference.

182
00:10:57.732 --> 00:10:58.652
And here we see

183
00:10:59.792 --> 00:11:03.762
now well-recognized U-shaped patterns for colorectal cancer.

184
00:11:05.072 --> 00:11:08.752
The risk declines among those born in the first half of the

185
00:11:08.792 --> 00:11:12.192
century and bottoms out among those born in the

186
00:11:12.202 --> 00:11:15.932
'50s and then rises among those

187
00:11:15.952 --> 00:11:18.572
born in second half of the century.

188
00:11:19.692 --> 00:11:23.532
And this shape suggests that people born in the

189
00:11:23.542 --> 00:11:24.112
'80s

190
00:11:25.012 --> 00:11:28.872
may face about a 50% higher risk of developing

191
00:11:28.892 --> 00:11:32.552
colorectal cancer as they age, compared with

192
00:11:32.632 --> 00:11:34.132
those born in the '50s.

193
00:11:37.432 --> 00:11:41.372
And on the right, this is a complementary view of how this birth

194
00:11:41.472 --> 00:11:44.732
cohort trend translates to age-specific

195
00:11:44.832 --> 00:11:48.652
trends for the last 20 years, measured as annual

196
00:11:48.712 --> 00:11:49.712
percent change.

197
00:11:52.712 --> 00:11:56.212
The blue box, the earlier decline among

198
00:11:56.352 --> 00:12:00.292
older birth cohorts, drives the falling rates

199
00:12:00.312 --> 00:12:04.296
of colorectal cancer among older adults.While the

200
00:12:04.376 --> 00:12:07.696
progressive increase among younger recent

201
00:12:07.776 --> 00:12:11.396
generations drives the rising early-onset

202
00:12:11.436 --> 00:12:14.776
colorectal cancer among those under age

203
00:12:14.916 --> 00:12:15.696
55.

204
00:12:17.456 --> 00:12:20.636
The favorable trends of colorectal cancer among older

205
00:12:20.716 --> 00:12:24.436
adults has been attributed to improvement in

206
00:12:24.456 --> 00:12:28.196
lifestyle factors such as reduction in smoking, and

207
00:12:28.256 --> 00:12:32.176
importantly, the widespread uptake of colorectal

208
00:12:32.256 --> 00:12:34.936
cancer screening since the late '90s.

209
00:12:37.156 --> 00:12:40.776
But the reasons for the rising risk among younger generation

210
00:12:42.076 --> 00:12:45.856
remain less clear, with many in this room leading the effort

211
00:12:46.196 --> 00:12:47.116
to uncover them.

212
00:12:49.816 --> 00:12:53.776
Just published last week, this study reveals

213
00:12:53.796 --> 00:12:57.685
a stark social disparity on early-onset colorectal

214
00:12:57.756 --> 00:12:59.876
cancer mortality in the United States.

215
00:13:01.456 --> 00:13:03.016
This graph shows

216
00:13:04.396 --> 00:13:08.096
the past 30-year mortality trends among young men

217
00:13:08.836 --> 00:13:10.416
by educational attainment.

218
00:13:11.816 --> 00:13:13.736
While the mortality has increased

219
00:13:14.816 --> 00:13:18.326
across both levels, it has been persistently

220
00:13:18.396 --> 00:13:22.386
higher among young men with lower education, and

221
00:13:22.416 --> 00:13:25.596
the gap between groups is widening over time.

222
00:13:27.016 --> 00:13:30.016
A simple finding, but one with profound

223
00:13:30.176 --> 00:13:31.076
implications,

224
00:13:32.256 --> 00:13:35.286
not just for emerging risk factors, but also

225
00:13:36.236 --> 00:13:39.936
for how our healthcare systems serve young adults

226
00:13:40.096 --> 00:13:42.096
diagnosed with cancer.

227
00:13:44.576 --> 00:13:48.036
Rising early-onset colorectal cancer incidence has now been reported

228
00:13:48.576 --> 00:13:52.436
in at least 26 countries, and two patterns emerge.

229
00:13:53.156 --> 00:13:55.376
In many high-income Western countries,

230
00:13:56.636 --> 00:14:00.456
the increase is limited to young adults, while the

231
00:14:00.476 --> 00:14:03.756
rates are falling or stabilizing among older adults.

232
00:14:05.696 --> 00:14:08.876
In others, predominantly in Latin America and Asia,

233
00:14:09.636 --> 00:14:13.156
the rates are increasing in both young and old adults.

234
00:14:15.276 --> 00:14:18.336
We see similar patterns in mortality as well.

235
00:14:19.056 --> 00:14:20.376
Here are two examples.

236
00:14:21.176 --> 00:14:24.756
In Australia, the increase of mortality

237
00:14:24.766 --> 00:14:26.876
is confined to young adults.

238
00:14:27.696 --> 00:14:28.256
In Chile,

239
00:14:29.276 --> 00:14:31.556
both age groups are being affected.

240
00:14:35.556 --> 00:14:39.216
International comparisons of generational

241
00:14:39.276 --> 00:14:42.076
cancer risk are limited, but they may

242
00:14:42.196 --> 00:14:45.916
offer an important insights into underlying

243
00:14:45.996 --> 00:14:49.236
drivers. In countries including Australia,

244
00:14:49.636 --> 00:14:53.116
UK, Canada, and France, we see a similar

245
00:14:53.316 --> 00:14:54.336
U-shaped pattern.

246
00:14:56.096 --> 00:14:56.956
Consistently,

247
00:14:58.856 --> 00:15:00.976
robust signals across countries,

248
00:15:01.876 --> 00:15:05.516
despite differences in their environment and healthcare

249
00:15:05.576 --> 00:15:08.116
systems, suggesting

250
00:15:08.136 --> 00:15:12.036
progressively rising colorectal cancer incidence

251
00:15:12.136 --> 00:15:14.436
among those born in '70s and '80s.

252
00:15:16.636 --> 00:15:19.796
In second group of countries including Chile, Brazil,

253
00:15:20.216 --> 00:15:23.516
Philippine, and South Africa, there is no earlier

254
00:15:23.576 --> 00:15:24.245
decline,

255
00:15:25.116 --> 00:15:28.616
only the steady rise of the risk across the successive

256
00:15:28.656 --> 00:15:29.376
generations.

257
00:15:30.465 --> 00:15:32.216
In this second group of countries,

258
00:15:33.476 --> 00:15:37.096
rising risk of colorectal cancer among younger generation

259
00:15:37.856 --> 00:15:39.936
creates a compounding challenge.

260
00:15:40.556 --> 00:15:44.436
It's adding to the substantially large and still

261
00:15:44.446 --> 00:15:47.656
growing mortality burden among older adults.

262
00:15:49.796 --> 00:15:52.996
Let me turn to breast cancer, where the story becomes more nuanced.

263
00:15:54.046 --> 00:15:57.816
Here we see clear divergence of birth cohort trend by

264
00:15:58.256 --> 00:15:59.516
breast cancer subtype.

265
00:16:01.016 --> 00:16:04.716
The red line on the left, the estrogen receptor-positive cancer.

266
00:16:05.176 --> 00:16:09.056
The risk is relatively stable until mid-centuries,

267
00:16:09.576 --> 00:16:13.376
but it rises among younger generation, peaking in

268
00:16:13.396 --> 00:16:15.656
women born in 1990.

269
00:16:16.796 --> 00:16:18.236
And this birth cohort trend

270
00:16:19.256 --> 00:16:23.176
translates to faster increase of breast cancer

271
00:16:23.236 --> 00:16:27.186
among younger women, although the rates are increasing in older

272
00:16:27.256 --> 00:16:27.936
women as well.

273
00:16:29.296 --> 00:16:32.336
In contrast, estrogen receptor-negative cancer,

274
00:16:33.196 --> 00:16:36.796
the cohort rates declines across the successive

275
00:16:36.856 --> 00:16:40.796
generations. This analysis does not include

276
00:16:40.896 --> 00:16:44.356
any risk factor data, but this diverging pattern

277
00:16:44.536 --> 00:16:47.956
suggests that breast cancer subtype-specific risk

278
00:16:48.076 --> 00:16:51.416
factors might be shifting in opposite direction.

279
00:16:55.156 --> 00:16:58.696
Endometrial cancer shows a similar pattern as

280
00:16:58.796 --> 00:17:01.156
estrogen receptor-positive breast cancer.

281
00:17:02.316 --> 00:17:05.556
The highest risk among the youngest birth cohort,

282
00:17:05.876 --> 00:17:09.536
suggesting each successive generation of women

283
00:17:10.517 --> 00:17:13.896
may be entering their adulthood with a higher

284
00:17:13.936 --> 00:17:17.576
baseline risk compared with their mother's generation.

285
00:17:19.056 --> 00:17:22.885
And this birth cohort trend, again, mirrored by

286
00:17:22.916 --> 00:17:26.356
faster increase of endometrial cancer among younger women.

287
00:17:28.036 --> 00:17:31.856
Now with thyroid cancer, similar but importantly

288
00:17:31.936 --> 00:17:32.356
different.

289
00:17:33.956 --> 00:17:36.756
Birth cohort trend increase in a linear

290
00:17:36.816 --> 00:17:40.796
fashion without a clear change in the slope.

291
00:17:42.596 --> 00:17:46.456
And thyroid cancer rise fairly uniformly across

292
00:17:46.636 --> 00:17:47.376
all ages.

293
00:17:48.556 --> 00:17:52.516
This pattern suggests the increase of thyroid cancer is

294
00:17:52.576 --> 00:17:56.016
not tied to a particular generation.

295
00:17:56.476 --> 00:18:00.176
Rather, it's a period effect, something that affects all age

296
00:18:00.296 --> 00:18:00.576
groups

297
00:18:00.636 --> 00:18:04.840
simultaneously.And

298
00:18:04.860 --> 00:18:07.740
this pattern also highlights an important

299
00:18:09.080 --> 00:18:10.910
limitation of APC modeling.

300
00:18:11.780 --> 00:18:15.630
Even when the underlying driver is a period effect, the model can still

301
00:18:15.680 --> 00:18:18.920
produce what appears to be a generational difference.

302
00:18:20.270 --> 00:18:23.780
This can mislead us unless we pay close

303
00:18:23.820 --> 00:18:27.140
attention to the shape of the curve, which we can test

304
00:18:27.340 --> 00:18:29.280
statistically.

305
00:18:30.120 --> 00:18:33.900
Here we see a similar pattern in pancreatic neuroendocrine

306
00:18:33.910 --> 00:18:34.300
tumor.

307
00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:39.080
Birth cohort trend increases in a linear fashion

308
00:18:40.300 --> 00:18:41.780
and rates increase

309
00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:45.000
fairly evenly across all age groups.

310
00:18:45.540 --> 00:18:48.720
In contrast, pancreatic adenocarcinoma

311
00:18:49.380 --> 00:18:53.140
is primarily rising among older adults.

312
00:18:53.940 --> 00:18:57.580
Together, these patterns suggest that

313
00:18:58.340 --> 00:19:01.920
the rise of pancreatic cancer overall reported among all

314
00:19:01.960 --> 00:19:05.620
younger adults in the United States is likely driven

315
00:19:05.680 --> 00:19:07.560
by increase in pancreatic

316
00:19:10.180 --> 00:19:11.560
neuroendocrine tumors.

317
00:19:13.390 --> 00:19:16.840
This graph shows instance trends of neuroendocrine

318
00:19:17.020 --> 00:19:17.860
neoplasms

319
00:19:18.880 --> 00:19:21.320
for last 25 years in the United States.

320
00:19:21.880 --> 00:19:24.800
And there is a clear surge since 2013,

321
00:19:25.710 --> 00:19:27.680
especially for localized disease.

322
00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:32.680
And this timing closely aligns with the updates in the

323
00:19:32.840 --> 00:19:35.420
WHO classification for digestive

324
00:19:36.760 --> 00:19:40.690
system cancers, and also ICD coding changes

325
00:19:40.720 --> 00:19:43.860
that expanded the definition of neuroendocrine tumors.

326
00:19:45.400 --> 00:19:47.940
The increasing diagnosis of neuroendocrine tumor

327
00:19:48.820 --> 00:19:52.700
is affecting trends in several GI cancers to varying

328
00:19:52.720 --> 00:19:56.600
degrees. So moving forward, it's important to

329
00:19:56.640 --> 00:19:59.570
separate these cancers in our analysis to better

330
00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:03.520
capture more etiologically relevant subtype.

331
00:20:05.160 --> 00:20:06.000
Stepping back,

332
00:20:07.340 --> 00:20:08.320
we see a pattern.

333
00:20:09.160 --> 00:20:13.000
Some cancers like colorectal, estrogen receptor-positive or

334
00:20:13.040 --> 00:20:16.800
endometrial cancer, shows increases in

335
00:20:16.860 --> 00:20:19.960
birth cohort trend in younger generations,

336
00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:23.689
leading to faster or confined

337
00:20:23.920 --> 00:20:26.730
increases of those cancers in young adults,

338
00:20:27.240 --> 00:20:29.600
consistent with birth cohort effect.

339
00:20:30.260 --> 00:20:34.160
Others, like thyroid cancer or pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor,

340
00:20:34.740 --> 00:20:38.640
shows uniform rises across age groups pointing to

341
00:20:38.700 --> 00:20:39.840
a period effect.

342
00:20:41.060 --> 00:20:44.860
But in reality, this may not be a simple cohort

343
00:20:44.920 --> 00:20:46.480
versus period stories.

344
00:20:47.860 --> 00:20:50.860
Most cancers likely fall somewhere in between

345
00:20:51.840 --> 00:20:55.640
with the relative contribution of each varying by cancer

346
00:20:55.700 --> 00:20:59.390
types, reflecting the complex and heterogeneous

347
00:20:59.520 --> 00:21:00.620
nature of cancer.

348
00:21:02.260 --> 00:21:06.020
In other words, even for cancers with a strong birth cohort effect,

349
00:21:07.560 --> 00:21:11.180
we cannot fully discount the influence of increasingly

350
00:21:11.220 --> 00:21:14.940
sensitive diagnostics and expanding use of these

351
00:21:15.020 --> 00:21:16.580
technologies over time.

352
00:21:17.500 --> 00:21:18.360
On the flip side,

353
00:21:19.500 --> 00:21:23.360
not all thyroid cancers or incidentally diagnosed cancers

354
00:21:23.440 --> 00:21:27.360
are simply over-diagnosis. We know that some

355
00:21:27.400 --> 00:21:30.840
early-stage cancers do carry metastatic

356
00:21:30.880 --> 00:21:31.460
potential.

357
00:21:33.980 --> 00:21:37.720
Let me turn to a more encouraging side of the story.

358
00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:41.420
Some cancers show lower risk among younger generation,

359
00:21:42.080 --> 00:21:45.860
including lung cancer, other smoking-related cancer,

360
00:21:46.080 --> 00:21:49.140
cervical cancer, lymphomas, and melanoma.

361
00:21:50.129 --> 00:21:53.900
And in the last few slides, I'd like to highlight lung and

362
00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:54.880
cervical cancer.

363
00:21:57.100 --> 00:22:00.920
The risk reduction in lung cancer in younger generation

364
00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:05.500
is a striking example and reflects one of

365
00:22:05.580 --> 00:22:08.820
the greatest public health success in the United States,

366
00:22:09.920 --> 00:22:12.180
the reduction in smoking prevalence.

367
00:22:14.160 --> 00:22:16.480
But the progress is never even

368
00:22:17.740 --> 00:22:21.220
across countries or subpopulations with some groups

369
00:22:21.479 --> 00:22:22.840
always falling behind.

370
00:22:24.260 --> 00:22:28.100
This graph shows lung cancer incidence rates

371
00:22:28.160 --> 00:22:30.960
as projected when each birth cohort

372
00:22:31.660 --> 00:22:33.080
reaches age 60,

373
00:22:34.020 --> 00:22:35.780
in a few countries by sex.

374
00:22:37.420 --> 00:22:38.840
A clear pattern emerge.

375
00:22:39.920 --> 00:22:42.500
The risk of lung cancer declines

376
00:22:43.400 --> 00:22:43.940
in men

377
00:22:44.920 --> 00:22:48.420
but increased or just plateaued in women.

378
00:22:49.340 --> 00:22:50.080
As a result,

379
00:22:50.900 --> 00:22:54.840
the sex gap in lung cancer risk narrows

380
00:22:54.900 --> 00:22:56.440
among younger generation,

381
00:22:58.240 --> 00:23:00.830
starting among baby boomers in the Netherlands,

382
00:23:01.880 --> 00:23:03.480
Generation X in France,

383
00:23:04.300 --> 00:23:07.040
millennials in South Korea, and

384
00:23:07.900 --> 00:23:10.960
has not yet appeared, but probably younger in Belarus.

385
00:23:12.010 --> 00:23:15.640
And these patterns send a signal about future

386
00:23:15.740 --> 00:23:16.200
burden of

387
00:23:17.200 --> 00:23:18.000
lung cancer.

388
00:23:19.340 --> 00:23:23.200
Without stronger tobacco control for younger generations

389
00:23:23.300 --> 00:23:26.700
of all genders, the progress will slow

390
00:23:27.380 --> 00:23:31.200
and then burden will increasingly shift toward women.

391
00:23:34.900 --> 00:23:38.740
The birth cohort perspective can also guide

392
00:23:39.260 --> 00:23:42.420
prevention strategies, and here is one example.

393
00:23:42.980 --> 00:23:45.140
Tobacco-free generation policy.

394
00:23:46.280 --> 00:23:50.260
A shift from age-based sales ban to birth year

395
00:23:50.420 --> 00:23:50.800
cutoff,

396
00:23:51.720 --> 00:23:55.340
so those born after a certain year can

397
00:23:55.420 --> 00:23:58.660
never legally purchase nicotine products.

398
00:24:00.240 --> 00:24:03.580
Not an abrupt ban, but a gradual path

399
00:24:04.460 --> 00:24:04.540
to

400
00:24:07.260 --> 00:24:10.860
eliminate exposures altogether from

401
00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:14.940
future generations.And finally, cervical

402
00:24:14.980 --> 00:24:18.660
cancer. This graph shows cervical cancer incidence

403
00:24:18.740 --> 00:24:22.620
rates as projected when each birth cohort reaches age 30.

404
00:24:24.260 --> 00:24:25.700
And here we see a glimpse

405
00:24:26.700 --> 00:24:29.320
how prevention efforts are reshaping the future.

406
00:24:31.040 --> 00:24:34.540
After gradual declines, the risk has fallen

407
00:24:35.140 --> 00:24:38.040
steeply, beginning with women born in

408
00:24:38.080 --> 00:24:39.200
1988,

409
00:24:40.480 --> 00:24:44.020
coinciding with one of the first birth years

410
00:24:44.040 --> 00:24:46.640
eligible for HPV vaccination.

411
00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:48.480
As a result,

412
00:24:50.980 --> 00:24:54.760
women born in '90s now have

413
00:24:54.900 --> 00:24:58.220
less than half the risk of those born in the '70s.

414
00:24:58.840 --> 00:25:02.480
A remarkable difference between birth cohorts

415
00:25:03.120 --> 00:25:05.640
born just 20 years apart.

416
00:25:07.520 --> 00:25:08.180
But globally,

417
00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:14.280
the progress is not even. In countries that implemented

418
00:25:14.700 --> 00:25:17.880
HPV vaccination early, before 2010,

419
00:25:18.640 --> 00:25:18.859
they are

420
00:25:20.620 --> 00:25:23.820
seeing very similar benefits in younger generation,

421
00:25:24.760 --> 00:25:28.620
but others with a delayed or limited rollout are

422
00:25:28.660 --> 00:25:28.960
not.

423
00:25:30.920 --> 00:25:32.840
This is yet another clear signal.

424
00:25:38.040 --> 00:25:40.580
The global disparities in cervical cancer

425
00:25:42.660 --> 00:25:45.820
may not only persist but also widen

426
00:25:46.420 --> 00:25:50.400
unless we expand the access to HPV vaccination

427
00:25:50.460 --> 00:25:54.080
and cervical cancer screening where they are needed the most.

428
00:25:56.340 --> 00:26:00.040
All in all, these examples highlight the strength and

429
00:26:00.100 --> 00:26:03.520
limitations of birth cohort analysis or APC modeling.

430
00:26:04.740 --> 00:26:08.700
When it's grounded in high-quality population-based cancer registry

431
00:26:08.740 --> 00:26:12.460
data, it enables to detect generational

432
00:26:12.520 --> 00:26:16.480
shift in risk and identify birth cohorts at

433
00:26:16.560 --> 00:26:20.140
higher risk, generate hypothesis on early life

434
00:26:20.200 --> 00:26:23.259
exposure, and reveal the impact of prevention.

435
00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:24.520
However,

436
00:26:26.240 --> 00:26:28.300
it's fundamentally descriptive

437
00:26:29.640 --> 00:26:33.500
and any inference is ecological at best.

438
00:26:34.300 --> 00:26:35.820
Importantly, this modeling

439
00:26:36.640 --> 00:26:40.340
cannot fully isolate cohort patterns free from

440
00:26:41.020 --> 00:26:44.700
period influences. So we want to be cautious in using this

441
00:26:44.740 --> 00:26:48.180
framework. Findings are highly context-specific,

442
00:26:48.620 --> 00:26:51.800
varying by countries, sub-population, and cancer subtypes.

443
00:26:52.380 --> 00:26:56.250
Like any modeling approach, it relies on assumptions and

444
00:26:56.360 --> 00:26:57.560
carries uncertainties.

445
00:26:58.500 --> 00:27:02.060
So I see birth cohort analysis not as a final answer,

446
00:27:02.420 --> 00:27:06.200
but as a useful lens that help us see better what's

447
00:27:06.300 --> 00:27:07.220
really changing.

448
00:27:08.840 --> 00:27:10.300
Here are a few takeaways.

449
00:27:11.160 --> 00:27:13.680
Again, cancer trends in young adults

450
00:27:15.160 --> 00:27:18.920
serve as early signals for future burden of cancer.

451
00:27:21.080 --> 00:27:24.840
Birth cohort framework is especially well-suited to

452
00:27:24.860 --> 00:27:28.680
studying cancer trends in young adults and separating signal

453
00:27:28.740 --> 00:27:32.720
from noise, as it captures early life exposures

454
00:27:33.200 --> 00:27:33.780
and also

455
00:27:34.660 --> 00:27:37.820
offer a fair comparison of the risk across generations.

456
00:27:39.560 --> 00:27:43.220
Generational cancer risk can move both directions.

457
00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:47.900
Rising risk among younger generation signal emerging

458
00:27:48.400 --> 00:27:50.860
risk factors, while falling risk

459
00:27:52.440 --> 00:27:54.700
demonstrates the power of prevention.

460
00:27:57.560 --> 00:28:01.500
Rising incidence of cancers among young adults does

461
00:28:01.510 --> 00:28:03.540
not reflect a single story.

462
00:28:04.840 --> 00:28:08.760
Some cancers likely represent the true shift

463
00:28:09.120 --> 00:28:12.200
in cancer risk among younger generations, but others

464
00:28:13.340 --> 00:28:17.040
are more likely about changes in diagnostic intensity

465
00:28:17.580 --> 00:28:20.700
and evolving disease classification of our time.

466
00:28:21.520 --> 00:28:25.280
Finally, future gains and disparities are already taking

467
00:28:25.400 --> 00:28:29.060
shapes in younger generations, from the widening social gap

468
00:28:29.280 --> 00:28:30.440
in early onset

469
00:28:31.500 --> 00:28:34.960
colorectal cancer mortality in the United States and also

470
00:28:36.360 --> 00:28:39.140
global disparities in cervical cancer prevention.

471
00:28:40.520 --> 00:28:42.080
So what should we do with these signals?

472
00:28:42.320 --> 00:28:45.360
These are not just warnings, these are also opportunities.

473
00:28:46.920 --> 00:28:50.300
Waiting until adulthood for prevention may be too late.

474
00:28:50.660 --> 00:28:53.540
We want to start primary prevention earlier,

475
00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:57.560
and we need a deeper understanding on early life

476
00:28:58.800 --> 00:29:02.580
risk factors so the prevention can be more timely, effective, and

477
00:29:02.660 --> 00:29:03.280
precise.

478
00:29:04.520 --> 00:29:06.860
Research community has a responsibility

479
00:29:07.920 --> 00:29:11.680
to distinguish and communicate better the underlying

480
00:29:11.740 --> 00:29:15.640
drivers behind rising cancer incidence in young adults.

481
00:29:15.700 --> 00:29:19.670
This attribution is critical to set priorities and

482
00:29:20.280 --> 00:29:22.920
respond effectively. Finally,

483
00:29:24.360 --> 00:29:27.680
cancer disparities found among younger generations

484
00:29:28.140 --> 00:29:32.100
deserve urgent attention because disadvantages that

485
00:29:32.200 --> 00:29:35.500
start early in life often persist a lifetime

486
00:29:36.580 --> 00:29:39.120
and deepen future health disparities.

487
00:29:40.360 --> 00:29:44.220
Before I close, I'd like to acknowledge the tremendous efforts

488
00:29:44.300 --> 00:29:47.040
of population-based cancer registries worldwide.

489
00:29:47.540 --> 00:29:51.200
Behind every trend shown today are decades of work

490
00:29:51.400 --> 00:29:54.190
supported by government funding and international

491
00:29:54.320 --> 00:29:57.700
agencies. Sustaining this commitment is vital

492
00:29:59.060 --> 00:30:03.020
to tracking the progress we made against cancer and

493
00:30:03.100 --> 00:30:06.480
identifying the remaining challenges, therefore,

494
00:30:08.140 --> 00:30:10.640
better informing cancer prevention and control.

495
00:30:13.460 --> 00:30:17.140
Finally, I'd like to acknowledge my colleagues and collaborators,

496
00:30:18.140 --> 00:30:22.010
especially a few by name. Qinzhi Zhang, Kieran Kelly, our outstanding

497
00:30:22.040 --> 00:30:24.640
associate scientists. Philip Rosenberg,

498
00:30:25.240 --> 00:30:28.740
whose pioneering work in APC modeling has

499
00:30:28.760 --> 00:30:32.564
deeply shapedMuch of this work. Freddie Bray,

500
00:30:33.684 --> 00:30:36.503
for his leadership in global cancer surveillance.

501
00:30:37.004 --> 00:30:37.684
And finally,

502
00:30:39.404 --> 00:30:43.004
senior colleagues at the American Cancer Society, Ahmedin

503
00:30:43.044 --> 00:30:44.564
Jamal and Rebecca Siegel,

504
00:30:45.424 --> 00:30:48.404
for their invaluable insights and leadership in the field.

505
00:30:48.724 --> 00:30:49.444
Thank you very much.

506
00:30:59.444 --> 00:31:02.924
Thank you, Dr. Sung, for that incredibly illuminating talk

507
00:31:03.684 --> 00:31:07.364
and being able to really identify for us the importance of population

508
00:31:07.444 --> 00:31:11.344
surveillance data, really understanding what's beneath the headlines for this

509
00:31:11.364 --> 00:31:13.324
phenomenon of early-onset cancers.

510
00:31:14.344 --> 00:31:17.174
And as Dr. Sung had nicely illustrated,

511
00:31:17.984 --> 00:31:21.734
perhaps the most striking data with respect to early-onset cancer that's

512
00:31:21.764 --> 00:31:24.984
emerged as an early signal has been in colorectal cancer.

513
00:31:26.024 --> 00:31:29.464
So my task in this talk is to really dive more deeply into colorectal

514
00:31:29.524 --> 00:31:33.444
cancer to help you understand where the state of the field is with respect to

515
00:31:33.484 --> 00:31:37.284
epidemiology and understanding risk factors for early-onset colorectal

516
00:31:37.324 --> 00:31:40.984
cancer, with an eye toward how we can move from those

517
00:31:41.044 --> 00:31:44.424
correlations and association studies to causative

518
00:31:44.484 --> 00:31:48.074
interpretation and ultimately to a landscape in which we can

519
00:31:48.204 --> 00:31:50.204
lead to preventive interventions.

520
00:31:52.984 --> 00:31:56.804
So I want to first start by laying out where we think we are

521
00:31:56.884 --> 00:32:00.784
with colorectal cancer. And I think among early-onset cancers, we are perhaps the

522
00:32:00.844 --> 00:32:04.504
farthest along with respect to understanding at least some risk factors for

523
00:32:04.524 --> 00:32:05.784
early-onset disease.

524
00:32:06.664 --> 00:32:10.444
This slide is just a summary of some of the risk factors that we've uncovered

525
00:32:10.454 --> 00:32:14.194
through epidemiological studies in our group at Mass General Hospital, but

526
00:32:14.264 --> 00:32:17.094
also Dr. Yin Cao's group at Washington University.

527
00:32:17.964 --> 00:32:21.884
These risk factors include obesity, metabolic comorbid conditions,

528
00:32:21.984 --> 00:32:25.464
diabetes, fatty liver, sedentary behavior,

529
00:32:26.224 --> 00:32:29.744
drinking patterns, low vitamin D, sulfur

530
00:32:29.804 --> 00:32:31.864
microbial diet or microbiome,

531
00:32:32.684 --> 00:32:36.174
sugar-sweetened beverages, and poor diet quality.

532
00:32:37.444 --> 00:32:41.324
Many of these risk factors cluster around metabolic dysfunction, which

533
00:32:41.363 --> 00:32:43.454
I'll delve into in more detail in a moment.

534
00:32:45.004 --> 00:32:48.933
I think what's been important about these studies is that they have given us clues

535
00:32:49.004 --> 00:32:52.624
as to what might be changing in our environment that underlies this birth cohort

536
00:32:52.664 --> 00:32:54.324
effect that Dr. Sung had mentioned.

537
00:32:55.564 --> 00:32:59.004
And then I think, in particular, what's really important is how we can take these

538
00:32:59.064 --> 00:33:02.904
association studies and try to develop them into a better understanding of what's

539
00:33:02.964 --> 00:33:05.904
happening causally in the field, again, with an eye

540
00:33:05.964 --> 00:33:07.614
toward prevention.

541
00:33:08.644 --> 00:33:12.153
Many of these associations have been corroborated in other cohorts, but what's

542
00:33:12.164 --> 00:33:15.744
really needed is additional studies to really identify what's causal

543
00:33:16.344 --> 00:33:20.334
so that we can develop actionable preventive interventions among younger

544
00:33:20.444 --> 00:33:21.194
generations.

545
00:33:23.404 --> 00:33:27.044
So to this end, Dr. Cao and I were fortunate to pull

546
00:33:27.104 --> 00:33:30.713
together this incredible team of investigators called Team

547
00:33:30.784 --> 00:33:34.504
Prospect, which was supported by Cancer Grand Challenges two years ago to

548
00:33:34.584 --> 00:33:38.524
tackle the question of why do we see a rising incidence of early-onset

549
00:33:38.624 --> 00:33:42.204
cancer. And our focus is really on pathways, risk

550
00:33:42.264 --> 00:33:46.224
factors, and molecules to really prevent early-onset colorectal tumors.

551
00:33:48.304 --> 00:33:52.264
We've brought together a global team, and that's really essential because as Dr.

552
00:33:52.504 --> 00:33:56.213
Sung illustrated, early-onset colorectal cancer has become a global

553
00:33:56.244 --> 00:33:59.774
concern. And in addition, because it is such a vexing and

554
00:33:59.824 --> 00:34:03.424
challenging problem, we need to bring together thought leaders across different

555
00:34:03.444 --> 00:34:07.344
disciplines with diverse expertise to tackle this really difficult

556
00:34:07.364 --> 00:34:07.884
problem.

557
00:34:09.044 --> 00:34:12.864
So today, this presentation will be a summary of where we are with Team Prospect

558
00:34:13.404 --> 00:34:17.284
to kind of, again, give you a sense of where we are on the landscape and to be able

559
00:34:17.324 --> 00:34:21.234
to move forward again for the future as this team continues to progress in

560
00:34:21.265 --> 00:34:21.754
its work.

561
00:34:24.225 --> 00:34:28.024
So the framework by which Team Prospect really operates under is what we

562
00:34:28.084 --> 00:34:29.665
call a causal pyramid,

563
00:34:30.844 --> 00:34:34.384
where we basically have at the base of the pyramid life course

564
00:34:34.504 --> 00:34:38.205
epidemiology cohorts to really examine risk factors across a life

565
00:34:38.304 --> 00:34:41.984
course, which is really essential given that we know that cancers that

566
00:34:42.044 --> 00:34:45.685
arise earlier in life must be due to risk factors that happen

567
00:34:45.765 --> 00:34:46.544
earlier in life.

568
00:34:47.623 --> 00:34:51.495
In addition, we layer onto those studies a convergence of

569
00:34:51.544 --> 00:34:55.324
human and animal data to really get at a mechanistic understanding

570
00:34:55.404 --> 00:34:59.244
of how these associations may actually contribute to cancer

571
00:34:59.324 --> 00:34:59.624
risk.

572
00:35:00.844 --> 00:35:04.524
And then finally, we hope to ascend that causal pyramid to the apex to

573
00:35:04.544 --> 00:35:08.364
really get to the point of being able to develop interventions

574
00:35:08.444 --> 00:35:11.904
that can actually reverse these risk factors and lead to

575
00:35:12.004 --> 00:35:15.804
actionable solutions for patients and our families in younger

576
00:35:15.884 --> 00:35:16.604
generations.

577
00:35:17.564 --> 00:35:21.204
So going and trending across this causal pyramid from correlation to

578
00:35:21.304 --> 00:35:24.944
causation to prevention is really the mission of Team

579
00:35:25.024 --> 00:35:28.564
Prospect and where I think we need to go as a field when we tackle this early-onset

580
00:35:28.624 --> 00:35:29.444
cancer problem.

581
00:35:31.264 --> 00:35:33.844
So let's first start with correlation and association.

582
00:35:33.884 --> 00:35:37.704
Where are we today with respect to understanding early-onset risk factors?

583
00:35:37.724 --> 00:35:41.404
And again, that is really focused on using life course epidemiology

584
00:35:41.464 --> 00:35:45.444
cohorts. But that's really been a limitation of the field, is that there are

585
00:35:45.524 --> 00:35:49.204
very few life course epidemiology cohorts that are capable of answering

586
00:35:49.264 --> 00:35:51.984
questions like early-onset cancer.

587
00:35:52.024 --> 00:35:56.004
There are very few cohorts that have been developed with birth and early

588
00:35:56.124 --> 00:36:00.073
childhood in mind, and certainly cohorts that have been formed are not

589
00:36:00.104 --> 00:36:03.684
of sufficient size to really track people for a long enough period of time to

590
00:36:03.724 --> 00:36:07.704
develop a sufficient number of incident cases to really study them with

591
00:36:07.714 --> 00:36:09.384
a lot of rigor and reproducibility.

592
00:36:10.084 --> 00:36:13.864
So it's required us to be creative in trying to understand this phenomenon

593
00:36:14.004 --> 00:36:17.964
by pooling cohorts together but also leveraging existing cohorts so

594
00:36:18.004 --> 00:36:20.744
we can start to get some answers to these really pressing

595
00:36:20.844 --> 00:36:24.628
questions.So we really view early onset

596
00:36:24.668 --> 00:36:27.608
colorectal cancer, as I mentioned, as a life course disease.

597
00:36:27.948 --> 00:36:31.888
Because when we think about cancer risk in someone's 30s, 40s, and 50s, we

598
00:36:31.928 --> 00:36:35.908
have to think about what they're exposed to, not only in that age group, but also

599
00:36:35.948 --> 00:36:37.868
what they're exposed to earlier in life.

600
00:36:38.518 --> 00:36:42.408
And this is a concept that we actually reviewed recently in a review

601
00:36:42.468 --> 00:36:45.728
that was led by Mengxi Du, who is a junior faculty member in our group.

602
00:36:46.108 --> 00:36:49.148
And our focus was really on metabolic dysfunction, which

603
00:36:49.388 --> 00:36:52.288
arguably is perhaps the farthest

604
00:36:52.348 --> 00:36:56.128
along the path and from getting to early life course

605
00:36:56.188 --> 00:36:59.297
epidemiology to causality to prevention.

606
00:36:59.818 --> 00:37:03.588
And so my focus today will be on metabolic dysfunction and obesity as sort of

607
00:37:03.598 --> 00:37:07.548
a model for how we can think about life course studies to

608
00:37:07.608 --> 00:37:10.808
identify risk factors for early onset cancer that can be potentially

609
00:37:10.848 --> 00:37:11.628
intervenable.

610
00:37:13.208 --> 00:37:16.588
So let's really try to leverage what we can from existing data.

611
00:37:16.598 --> 00:37:20.578
And so much of what I'm going to present to you has been data that we've collected

612
00:37:20.578 --> 00:37:24.148
through really important, large epidemiological cohort studies

613
00:37:24.668 --> 00:37:27.738
that are based at Harvard, that have been funded for many years by the National

614
00:37:27.848 --> 00:37:31.468
Cancer Institute and other entities that really illustrate the value of

615
00:37:31.508 --> 00:37:34.628
population epidemiology data across decades of life.

616
00:37:35.628 --> 00:37:38.948
These are the very well-characterized and well-known Nurses' Health Studies 1 and

617
00:37:39.228 --> 00:37:39.248
2,

618
00:37:40.108 --> 00:37:43.508
as well as the Health Professionals Follow-up Studies, which collectively have

619
00:37:43.548 --> 00:37:47.258
enrolled over 250,000 individuals across several

620
00:37:47.348 --> 00:37:47.928
decades.

621
00:37:48.748 --> 00:37:52.408
And importantly, these really dedicated participants have given us very

622
00:37:52.418 --> 00:37:56.358
detailed information on their lifestyle every two years, as well as

623
00:37:56.368 --> 00:37:59.788
dietary information every four years, and have given us

624
00:37:59.828 --> 00:38:03.608
permission to track them for the incidence of colorectal cancer over time.

625
00:38:04.448 --> 00:38:07.808
In addition, we've tracked these participants for the incidence of colorectal

626
00:38:07.828 --> 00:38:11.148
adenoma, the principal precursor lesion of colorectal cancer.

627
00:38:12.058 --> 00:38:15.928
And so these studies are studies which have been very rich in data and have given

628
00:38:15.968 --> 00:38:19.858
us some clues as to what leads we should follow with respect to risk factors

629
00:38:19.868 --> 00:38:21.048
for early onset cancer.

630
00:38:23.188 --> 00:38:26.648
I think one of the important components of these studies is that they really do

631
00:38:27.328 --> 00:38:31.108
provide a snapshot of what's happening in the larger US

632
00:38:31.188 --> 00:38:34.928
population. As Dr. Song nicely showed, there is this

633
00:38:35.028 --> 00:38:38.508
U-shaped curve with colorectal cancer incidence and mortality, such that

634
00:38:38.548 --> 00:38:42.128
generations born before 1955 show a

635
00:38:42.168 --> 00:38:45.257
gradual decline in colorectal cancer incidence and mortality.

636
00:38:45.888 --> 00:38:49.757
But that decline reverses after 1955, such that we're starting to see

637
00:38:49.788 --> 00:38:53.317
these increasing rates of both cancer incidence and

638
00:38:53.368 --> 00:38:56.828
mortality across different birth cohort generations.

639
00:38:57.948 --> 00:39:01.768
So within the Nurses' Health Studies, in unpublished data led by Michael

640
00:39:01.788 --> 00:39:05.768
Fuchs and Cindy Zhang in our group, they've nicely showed that the Nurses'

641
00:39:05.828 --> 00:39:09.008
Health Studies do represent that same birth cohort, such that

642
00:39:09.428 --> 00:39:13.398
colorectal cancer incidence and mortality has fallen by birth cohorts in

643
00:39:13.428 --> 00:39:17.388
the Nurses' Health Studies, but then by 1950 have started to creep up as

644
00:39:17.428 --> 00:39:21.348
well. And collectively, we can use this sort of information to look at the

645
00:39:21.388 --> 00:39:24.888
compendium of data collected within these cohorts to understand what is sort of the

646
00:39:24.928 --> 00:39:28.868
environmental risk factors that have changed across these participants over

647
00:39:28.908 --> 00:39:32.708
time to provide us some insight into what might be underlying

648
00:39:32.718 --> 00:39:35.928
this birth cohort effect nationally.

649
00:39:37.048 --> 00:39:40.298
So let's first start with the easy questions, or not so easy questions, but at

650
00:39:40.328 --> 00:39:43.848
least the basic questions. What are some of the exposures that we see in adulthood

651
00:39:43.908 --> 00:39:45.788
that could be associated with early onset cancer?

652
00:39:45.868 --> 00:39:49.668
So let's first look at, for example, risk factors when someone's

653
00:39:49.688 --> 00:39:52.288
already an adult, in middle age or beyond.

654
00:39:54.148 --> 00:39:56.008
So this was one of the early studies that Dr.

655
00:39:56.248 --> 00:39:59.668
Cao led in using Nurses' Health Study 2 data, in which she

656
00:39:59.708 --> 00:40:03.688
examined midlife adiposity and its association with early onset

657
00:40:03.728 --> 00:40:05.528
cancer in the Nurses' Health Study 2.

658
00:40:06.388 --> 00:40:08.648
And what she found was that BMI

659
00:40:09.528 --> 00:40:12.488
at adulthood, when someone's already at middle age or beyond,

660
00:40:13.388 --> 00:40:16.208
was associated with a higher risk of early onset cancer.

661
00:40:16.348 --> 00:40:19.918
Specifically, individuals that were obese had a twofold higher incidence of early

662
00:40:20.028 --> 00:40:22.748
onset cancer compared to those who were non-obese.

663
00:40:23.288 --> 00:40:26.688
And this sort of obesity association in mid to late adulthood

664
00:40:27.128 --> 00:40:31.068
represents obesity at a single time point, but also represents

665
00:40:31.078 --> 00:40:34.088
a cumulative exposure to obesity over a life course.

666
00:40:34.648 --> 00:40:38.328
How do we know that? Well, we do need to maybe look at some data that has been

667
00:40:38.368 --> 00:40:40.348
collected during earlier adulthood.

668
00:40:41.058 --> 00:40:44.568
There are very few cohorts that have enrolled people in this sort of younger age

669
00:40:44.667 --> 00:40:48.648
range, but fortunately within the Nurses' Health Study 2, we also were

670
00:40:48.748 --> 00:40:50.668
able to ask our participants about

671
00:40:52.528 --> 00:40:56.128
their recall with respect to body mass index at an earlier phase in life.

672
00:40:56.788 --> 00:41:00.528
So Dr. Cao nicely showed that when you look at BMI at age

673
00:41:00.608 --> 00:41:04.548
18, there are also similar associations with early onset cancer.

674
00:41:05.388 --> 00:41:09.188
And specifically, even BMI that's not considered to be obese,

675
00:41:09.508 --> 00:41:13.168
but may be overweight or trending toward higher levels of body weight in the normal

676
00:41:13.208 --> 00:41:17.148
range, are linked with about a 1.6-fold higher incidence of early onset

677
00:41:17.188 --> 00:41:20.808
cancer compared to a referent category of normal weight.

678
00:41:21.428 --> 00:41:25.028
So even body mass index at 18 is a reflection of a risk factor

679
00:41:25.548 --> 00:41:29.448
of adiposity that could underlie the early onset, at least some of the

680
00:41:29.488 --> 00:41:31.927
early onset cancer risk we're seeing in our participants.

681
00:41:33.988 --> 00:41:37.748
But I think we want to also delve more deeply into other possibilities, and

682
00:41:37.808 --> 00:41:40.918
certainly, we have to also look at the possibility that

683
00:41:40.948 --> 00:41:44.088
exposure to overweight, obesity, or metabolic

684
00:41:44.148 --> 00:41:48.108
dysregulation at earlier phases of life similarly are important to

685
00:41:48.128 --> 00:41:49.808
consider when we think about cancer risk.

686
00:41:50.228 --> 00:41:53.948
And that includes obesity and overweight in childhood to adolescence,

687
00:41:54.568 --> 00:41:58.238
but even obesity and overweight in utero or in infancy,

688
00:41:58.608 --> 00:42:02.548
to even think about the possibility that some of this effect of metabolic

689
00:42:02.588 --> 00:42:06.428
dysregulation may be imprinted even before someone is born.

690
00:42:06.888 --> 00:42:10.618
And this is a hypothesis that also is important to consider in the field and will

691
00:42:10.668 --> 00:42:14.588
be explored more deeply by Dr. Alexandrov in a subsequent talk.

692
00:42:15.348 --> 00:42:19.188
But I think we do have some early evidence that even in utero exposure to

693
00:42:19.408 --> 00:42:23.248
obesity, adiposity, and an obesogenic environment may be linked to early

694
00:42:23.268 --> 00:42:27.168
onset cancer. As I mentioned, there is a dearth of data from birth

695
00:42:27.268 --> 00:42:31.132
cohorts, but we do have some clues.So within our Harvard

696
00:42:31.232 --> 00:42:34.562
cohort studies, we were also fortunate to leverage data collected

697
00:42:34.632 --> 00:42:37.412
among the members of our cohort's mothers.

698
00:42:38.172 --> 00:42:41.792
So during different time points across follow-up, we

699
00:42:41.932 --> 00:42:45.702
asked the participants in the cohort to give their mothers a questionnaire,

700
00:42:46.472 --> 00:42:50.352
and the mothers were asked, "What were you exposed to when you were pregnant with

701
00:42:50.392 --> 00:42:54.262
the participant?" and, "What were the participants

702
00:42:54.352 --> 00:42:58.272
like as kids, and what were they exposed to?" And so that gives us some clues

703
00:42:58.332 --> 00:43:02.112
as to potentially what's happening in early life among participants that are

704
00:43:02.132 --> 00:43:05.652
being tracked very closely for cancer incidents over time.

705
00:43:05.692 --> 00:43:09.592
And among these three cohorts, we had data from about 45,000 individuals.

706
00:43:10.692 --> 00:43:14.252
So here are some of the domains that we collect in our mother's questionnaire.

707
00:43:14.332 --> 00:43:17.612
We collect detailed information among the pregnancy factors

708
00:43:19.132 --> 00:43:21.921
among which the mothers were exposed to when they were pregnant with the

709
00:43:21.992 --> 00:43:25.872
participant. We also collected information about the participants when

710
00:43:25.912 --> 00:43:26.732
they were infants.

711
00:43:29.012 --> 00:43:32.972
So these are some early unpublished results, and this is work led by Fangyuan

712
00:43:32.992 --> 00:43:36.842
Zhang, who is a student at the School of Public Health at Harvard, who's

713
00:43:36.872 --> 00:43:39.752
supervised by Mingyang Song in our group.

714
00:43:39.792 --> 00:43:43.092
And what they found was quite interesting, that among

715
00:43:43.872 --> 00:43:43.982
the

716
00:43:44.832 --> 00:43:48.692
participants in our study, if their mothers gained more

717
00:43:48.712 --> 00:43:52.322
than 14 kilograms of weight during pregnancy, they had about a

718
00:43:52.392 --> 00:43:56.212
two-fold higher incidence of those participants having colorectal cancer

719
00:43:56.252 --> 00:44:00.052
subsequently during adulthood compared to the women

720
00:44:00.092 --> 00:44:03.952
whose pregnancies in which they had the least amount of weight gain during

721
00:44:03.992 --> 00:44:07.292
their pregnancy. So it does suggest that there's a potential

722
00:44:07.332 --> 00:44:11.312
effect of an obesogenic environment in the maternal

723
00:44:11.372 --> 00:44:15.032
setting, which may have a subsequent impact on cancer risk in the

724
00:44:15.072 --> 00:44:15.472
future.

725
00:44:17.652 --> 00:44:21.192
There are other exposure changes that have happened across birth cohorts within our

726
00:44:21.212 --> 00:44:24.722
studies. You can see here looking at TV watching, for example, in children,

727
00:44:25.252 --> 00:44:28.982
there's been a progressive increase in the amount of time people are

728
00:44:29.052 --> 00:44:32.972
spending in front of the TV, which is a surrogate for

729
00:44:33.212 --> 00:44:36.432
physical inactivity and for sedentary lifestyle.

730
00:44:36.492 --> 00:44:39.622
In addition, looking at pregnancy factors during

731
00:44:40.772 --> 00:44:44.532
pregnancy, we saw a gradual increase in alcohol intake across birth

732
00:44:44.612 --> 00:44:48.452
cohorts. And also among children, we saw an increase in processed

733
00:44:48.492 --> 00:44:51.892
meat intake over time. So there are these sort of birth cohort effects within our

734
00:44:51.932 --> 00:44:55.652
cohorts that we want to explore further in additional studies.

735
00:44:57.772 --> 00:45:01.252
So thinking about metabolic dysfunction obesity across the lifespan, we also want

736
00:45:01.272 --> 00:45:05.002
to consider other factors. For example, are there environmental factors,

737
00:45:05.112 --> 00:45:08.952
dietary factors, lifestyle factors, things that people are exposed to that may

738
00:45:08.992 --> 00:45:12.652
contribute to cancer risk and that may also be mediated through metabolic

739
00:45:12.672 --> 00:45:13.322
dysfunction?

740
00:45:14.972 --> 00:45:18.372
So one such factor is the consumption of ultra-processed foods.

741
00:45:18.412 --> 00:45:21.972
So ultra-processed food represents a type of food that

742
00:45:22.032 --> 00:45:25.652
undergoes a large amount of industrial processing, which

743
00:45:25.712 --> 00:45:29.572
includes the addition of a lot of preservatives, emulsifiers, oftentimes the

744
00:45:29.592 --> 00:45:33.152
addition of salt and high fructose corn syrup.

745
00:45:33.652 --> 00:45:37.272
And this type of food has been linked to a variety of metabolic

746
00:45:37.332 --> 00:45:40.812
disorders. And it's become also something that's been

747
00:45:41.172 --> 00:45:45.132
noticed to be upticking and trending across different age groups in the

748
00:45:45.192 --> 00:45:49.152
US population. In particular, among US youth across different age groups,

749
00:45:49.592 --> 00:45:52.812
there has been a substantial increase in ultra-processed food intake over the

750
00:45:52.892 --> 00:45:56.342
years, both in age groups, but also in different races and

751
00:45:56.392 --> 00:45:57.051
ethnicities.

752
00:45:58.452 --> 00:46:01.612
Ultra-processed food has been linked to factors that have also been linked to

753
00:46:01.632 --> 00:46:03.952
early-onset cancer. So this is work led by Dr.

754
00:46:04.032 --> 00:46:06.842
Du, and she found using a cohort called GUTS.

755
00:46:06.932 --> 00:46:09.772
This is a cohort of offspring of Nurses' Health Study Two

756
00:46:09.792 --> 00:46:13.592
participants that have been followed in childhood when they were between the

757
00:46:13.612 --> 00:46:17.382
ages of seven and 17. And what she showed in this study was

758
00:46:17.412 --> 00:46:21.192
that exposure to an even just 10% increase in

759
00:46:21.272 --> 00:46:24.942
ultra-processed food intake can result in substantial and

760
00:46:24.972 --> 00:46:28.632
significant increases in body mass index in children over different time

761
00:46:28.652 --> 00:46:32.292
periods. So there is a link, again, with ultra-processed food

762
00:46:32.352 --> 00:46:36.292
intake and metabolic disturbances in children, which could set

763
00:46:36.332 --> 00:46:38.072
them up for cancer risk in the future.

764
00:46:39.652 --> 00:46:42.932
Ultra-processed foods also been linked with a variety of metabolic conditions in

765
00:46:42.992 --> 00:46:46.912
adults, as shown in this meta-analysis, and that includes issues

766
00:46:46.952 --> 00:46:50.142
around metabolic health that have been well-characterized in other studies,

767
00:46:50.192 --> 00:46:53.912
including abdominal obesity, overweight, and type 2 diabetes.

768
00:46:55.192 --> 00:46:58.512
So to look at the association potentially of ultra-processed food with early-onset

769
00:46:58.592 --> 00:47:01.632
cancer, we asked this question within our Nurses Health Study Two cohort and

770
00:47:01.672 --> 00:47:05.612
specifically asked the question: Does ultra-processed food associate with a

771
00:47:05.652 --> 00:47:09.232
higher incidence of developing these precancerous polyps that we know lead to

772
00:47:09.272 --> 00:47:12.392
early-onset cancers or early-onset adenomas?

773
00:47:12.941 --> 00:47:16.932
And this is work that was led by Chun Wang in our group that was recently published

774
00:47:16.992 --> 00:47:20.972
that showed that the women who were consuming the highest quintile of

775
00:47:21.072 --> 00:47:24.452
ultra-processed food, as classified by what we call the NOVA

776
00:47:24.472 --> 00:47:28.402
classification, a commonly used scheme to classify ultra-processed food, they had

777
00:47:28.452 --> 00:47:32.252
about a 1.5-fold higher incidence of developing adenoma

778
00:47:32.292 --> 00:47:34.022
compared to those in the lowest quintile.

779
00:47:36.912 --> 00:47:40.412
So those were some early clues, again, as to what might be happening with respect

780
00:47:40.452 --> 00:47:43.012
to risk factor changes in different birth cohorts.

781
00:47:43.232 --> 00:47:46.632
Now we want to also understand not only what are associations but what are

782
00:47:46.692 --> 00:47:50.552
causal. And ideally, to be able to ascend the causal pyramid, we would

783
00:47:50.592 --> 00:47:54.572
love to have trial data, to have experimental data in humans, to be able

784
00:47:54.612 --> 00:47:58.472
to say these cancer risk factors linked to cancer when we actually give

785
00:47:58.492 --> 00:48:02.272
them to people or when we reverse those cancer risk factors in clinical trials.

786
00:48:02.672 --> 00:48:06.372
But those trials are incredibly difficult to do, and for anyone who does prevention

787
00:48:06.432 --> 00:48:10.192
research, really the difficulty in doing prevention trials is the

788
00:48:10.292 --> 00:48:13.912
length of time you need to follow individuals and the size of these cohorts.

789
00:48:14.392 --> 00:48:16.532
So we need to rely on another source of evidence.

790
00:48:16.632 --> 00:48:20.062
And so within our causal pyramid, we really wanted to use and

791
00:48:20.072 --> 00:48:23.792
utilize data from human and animal models to give us

792
00:48:23.852 --> 00:48:27.732
experimental data around mechanism that can allow us to infer causality.

793
00:48:27.982 --> 00:48:31.936
And so here are a couple of examples of thatSome of

794
00:48:31.976 --> 00:48:35.836
the key biological pathways that we think link metabolic disturbance

795
00:48:35.896 --> 00:48:39.566
with early onset cancer are outlined here, and again, summarized in our

796
00:48:39.596 --> 00:48:41.075
review that was recently published.

797
00:48:41.546 --> 00:48:45.476
This sort of axis of obesity and type 2 diabetes is linked to multiple

798
00:48:45.516 --> 00:48:49.376
risk factors and mechanisms that have been linked to early onset and late onset

799
00:48:49.436 --> 00:48:52.966
cancer. In particular, we've wanted to focus on insulin

800
00:48:53.016 --> 00:48:56.976
resistance because that seems to be a very consistent association across different

801
00:48:57.016 --> 00:49:00.076
epidemiological studies. So how do we use human

802
00:49:00.516 --> 00:49:04.446
biospecimens and translational data to really get at causality with

803
00:49:04.456 --> 00:49:05.936
respect to insulin resistance?

804
00:49:07.156 --> 00:49:10.705
So to do that, what we did was we took an approach where in our epidemiological

805
00:49:10.756 --> 00:49:12.696
cohorts, we have archived biospecimens.

806
00:49:12.756 --> 00:49:16.276
And in these archived biospecimens, we've also measured levels of

807
00:49:16.316 --> 00:49:19.076
C-peptide, which is a circulating biomarker of

808
00:49:19.116 --> 00:49:22.856
hyperinsulinemia. Within a sub-cohort of individuals in the

809
00:49:22.896 --> 00:49:26.726
Nurses' Health Study Too, we use measures of circulating

810
00:49:26.776 --> 00:49:30.596
C-peptide to indicate hyperinsulinemia and develop what we

811
00:49:30.636 --> 00:49:34.596
call an empirical lifestyle index for hyperinsulinemia, meaning what are

812
00:49:34.636 --> 00:49:38.576
the lifestyle and dietary factors that would predict who would have the highest

813
00:49:38.636 --> 00:49:40.296
levels of circulating insulin?

814
00:49:41.176 --> 00:49:44.356
And in this study, what Dr. Wang did was she

815
00:49:44.396 --> 00:49:48.296
examined this lifestyle index in relationship to early onset adenoma

816
00:49:48.336 --> 00:49:51.766
and found that the women in the study that had the highest

817
00:49:51.856 --> 00:49:55.616
predicted levels of circulating insulin had about a 1.3-fold higher

818
00:49:55.676 --> 00:49:59.546
incidence of early onset adenoma compared to those in the lowest quintile.

819
00:49:59.996 --> 00:50:03.616
So giving us some mechanistic associations that will allow us to

820
00:50:03.656 --> 00:50:06.456
connect ultra-processed food, for example, to early onset

821
00:50:06.516 --> 00:50:10.486
adenoma. And then as Dr. Sung had referenced, we also need

822
00:50:10.516 --> 00:50:14.336
to think more and more about our studies epidemiologically as needing to rely on

823
00:50:14.396 --> 00:50:17.976
exposures by birth cohort as opposed to arbitrary age

824
00:50:18.076 --> 00:50:21.736
cutoffs. And so we've also looked at these associations by birth cohort,

825
00:50:22.156 --> 00:50:25.976
and when we actually divide the cohort by birth cohort, we see that the individuals

826
00:50:26.016 --> 00:50:29.476
that were born in the later birth cohorts that really reflect this rising

827
00:50:29.556 --> 00:50:33.316
incidence of colorectal cancer, they were the group that had the

828
00:50:33.376 --> 00:50:37.016
higher incidence of adenoma when they were in the highest

829
00:50:37.096 --> 00:50:40.855
quintile of predicted hyperinsulinemia, whereas the earlier

830
00:50:40.956 --> 00:50:44.876
birth cohorts, that sort of hyperinsulinemia association really didn't seem to

831
00:50:44.916 --> 00:50:48.776
be as strong. So again, giving us some mechanistic clues as to what

832
00:50:48.816 --> 00:50:49.576
might be causal.

833
00:50:51.896 --> 00:50:55.336
There's also additional evidence that we can think about gut microbial

834
00:50:55.396 --> 00:50:59.316
dysbiosis as a convergent pathway by which these lifestyle factors may

835
00:50:59.376 --> 00:51:02.086
lead to early onset cancer as well as late onset cancer.

836
00:51:02.676 --> 00:51:06.296
And this will be delved into in a lot more detail in Dr. Alexandrov's talk.

837
00:51:06.356 --> 00:51:09.656
But just to give you some sense of potentially the association with metabolic

838
00:51:09.696 --> 00:51:13.656
disorders, I want to highlight this recent meta-analysis that was published

839
00:51:13.996 --> 00:51:17.816
last year by Nicola Segata's group, led by Gianmarco

840
00:51:17.856 --> 00:51:21.696
Pecino, a postdoctoral fellow and member of our PROSPECT team, where

841
00:51:21.756 --> 00:51:25.276
he showed that there are many different species that are

842
00:51:25.336 --> 00:51:29.036
correlated and anti-correlated with colorectal cancer.

843
00:51:29.046 --> 00:51:32.536
And I think what's important about this is that these potential

844
00:51:32.876 --> 00:51:36.356
species linked to colorectal cancer risk are also quite

845
00:51:36.416 --> 00:51:39.196
correlated with cardiometabolic risk.

846
00:51:39.816 --> 00:51:41.616
So if you see here on this

847
00:51:42.516 --> 00:51:46.056
graph, looking across different stages of colorectal cancer, there's a

848
00:51:46.116 --> 00:51:49.656
remarkable level of concordance, about a 20 to 30%

849
00:51:49.716 --> 00:51:53.566
concordance in the species that would predict cardiometabolic risk with

850
00:51:53.596 --> 00:51:57.236
colorectal cancer risk. So really suggesting that there is strong evidence

851
00:51:57.256 --> 00:52:01.116
supporting cardiometabolic changes as being a risk factor for early onset

852
00:52:01.196 --> 00:52:01.676
cancer.

853
00:52:03.776 --> 00:52:06.836
And then I want to turn finally to epigenetic regulation, because I think we're

854
00:52:06.856 --> 00:52:10.196
thinking more about the idea that not only are people exposed to different things

855
00:52:10.256 --> 00:52:13.716
across a life course, but also early life exposures may not need to be

856
00:52:13.756 --> 00:52:16.836
sustained across a life course to lead to future cancer risk.

857
00:52:17.836 --> 00:52:21.776
So what is the epigenome? The epigenome is an information processing

858
00:52:21.836 --> 00:52:25.356
hub where we consider environmental factors, for example, obesity,

859
00:52:25.876 --> 00:52:29.796
ultra-processed food, microbiome, as interacting with a cell,

860
00:52:30.216 --> 00:52:33.266
which subsequently leads to downstream expression of transcription

861
00:52:33.296 --> 00:52:37.146
factors that then preferentially bind to areas of chromatin on

862
00:52:37.176 --> 00:52:40.716
the genome that tends to regulate or upregulate

863
00:52:40.756 --> 00:52:42.516
expression of certain gene programs.

864
00:52:42.926 --> 00:52:46.546
So that epigenetic regulation of what's expressed in the cell is really

865
00:52:46.596 --> 00:52:50.575
critical for ultimately what's happening physiologically.

866
00:52:50.596 --> 00:52:54.416
So again, looking again at human animal convergent data,

867
00:52:54.816 --> 00:52:58.776
Jason Buenrostro's lab in our team PROSPECT in work led by Surya

868
00:52:59.516 --> 00:53:03.496
Nagaraja, a postdoctoral fellow, looked at an animal model of inflammation

869
00:53:03.536 --> 00:53:07.476
to assess, can inflammation be potentially an epigenetic

870
00:53:07.556 --> 00:53:11.496
mark on colorectal tissue that then leads and predisposes

871
00:53:11.536 --> 00:53:13.406
people to future cancer susceptibility?

872
00:53:14.136 --> 00:53:17.556
So in a mouse model in which they induce acute colitis with DSS,

873
00:53:18.076 --> 00:53:21.726
allow the mice to recover to a state of chronic colitis, and

874
00:53:21.776 --> 00:53:25.676
eventually to a state of complete recovery, they showed that you can have

875
00:53:25.736 --> 00:53:27.116
morphologically

876
00:53:28.196 --> 00:53:32.136
descriptive changes in which acute colitis does lead to epithelial changes that

877
00:53:32.156 --> 00:53:35.706
may become chronic, but once the colitis recovers, that

878
00:53:35.716 --> 00:53:39.036
mucosa or that colorectal epithelium begins to look

879
00:53:39.056 --> 00:53:42.856
morphologically normal. But taking tissue samples collected at these

880
00:53:42.866 --> 00:53:46.585
different time points, they're able to then look at both epigenetic

881
00:53:46.656 --> 00:53:50.536
regulation through single-cell ATAC-seq and also gene

882
00:53:50.596 --> 00:53:54.566
expression through single-cell RNA-seq through a novel method known as

883
00:53:54.596 --> 00:53:55.156
SHARE-seq.

884
00:53:55.976 --> 00:53:59.796
And with SHARE-seq data, they really showed that there is latent memory that's

885
00:53:59.836 --> 00:54:03.716
really encoded in chromatin. Specifically, in their model, what

886
00:54:03.736 --> 00:54:07.696
they showed was that when you measure chromatin accessibility, here measured

887
00:54:07.736 --> 00:54:11.696
by change in AP1 motif accessibility, you can see that

888
00:54:11.756 --> 00:54:15.196
in acute colitis, as it becomes chronic, there is a gradual

889
00:54:15.236 --> 00:54:18.526
increase in chromatin accessibility as measured by AP1,

890
00:54:19.556 --> 00:54:23.376
and that actually continues to be sustained even after that colitis

891
00:54:23.396 --> 00:54:24.116
has recovered.

892
00:54:25.316 --> 00:54:28.456
In contrast, when you look at transcription factor protein expression,

893
00:54:29.256 --> 00:54:32.656
as measured, for example, by the Fos transcription factor, you can see here in the

894
00:54:32.666 --> 00:54:36.326
acute setting, Fos protein expression increases and then

895
00:54:36.556 --> 00:54:39.546
does also increase with chronic colitis, but then when the colitis recovers,

896
00:54:39.636 --> 00:54:43.588
transcription factor expression goes back to normal.When you

897
00:54:43.608 --> 00:54:46.768
look at gene expression also the same pattern.

898
00:54:46.808 --> 00:54:50.308
You can see in the control setting and acute setting, there's a gradual

899
00:54:50.368 --> 00:54:54.198
increase in expression of certain pathways related to wound repair and

900
00:54:54.248 --> 00:54:57.628
inflammation. Those pathways may be back to normal and

901
00:54:57.668 --> 00:54:59.428
downregulated in the recovery state.

902
00:55:00.248 --> 00:55:03.988
But what's really changed and persisted is the idea that chromatin accessibility

903
00:55:04.048 --> 00:55:07.008
remains high even though

904
00:55:07.018 --> 00:55:10.788
morphologically the tissue is also healed, and

905
00:55:10.868 --> 00:55:14.738
also by protein expression and gene expression, the tissue looks normal.

906
00:55:15.308 --> 00:55:19.118
So that chromatin accessibility represents a potential molecular scar that

907
00:55:19.148 --> 00:55:22.428
could predispose to cancer in the future.

908
00:55:22.448 --> 00:55:25.088
And that's indeed what they show in a different mouse model.

909
00:55:25.188 --> 00:55:28.988
So looking at a mouse model of APC deletion, what they

910
00:55:29.008 --> 00:55:32.908
showed was that in mice that had no prior history of colitis or

911
00:55:32.948 --> 00:55:36.888
inflammation, when you basically delete APC, you do

912
00:55:36.948 --> 00:55:40.448
form adenomas. But in a mouse that had a history of chronic colitis,

913
00:55:40.548 --> 00:55:44.168
despite that colitis having resolved itself, that APC

914
00:55:44.188 --> 00:55:47.868
deletion does result in greater tumor burden.

915
00:55:47.948 --> 00:55:51.608
So this creates this model that we hope to pursue in more detail in Team

916
00:55:51.668 --> 00:55:54.948
Prospect, looking at a variety of lifestyle factors such as obesity,

917
00:55:55.148 --> 00:55:58.468
ultra-processed food microbiome, in which it can plausibly lead

918
00:55:58.528 --> 00:56:02.348
to an acute insult, maybe early in life, maybe

919
00:56:02.388 --> 00:56:06.148
somewhere in childhood or mid-adulthood, in which there is

920
00:56:06.208 --> 00:56:08.968
inflammation and damage that you can see in the tissue.

921
00:56:10.228 --> 00:56:13.568
And it leads to also a change in chromatin accessibility.

922
00:56:14.668 --> 00:56:18.008
And although the tissue may start to heal over time, as shown here,

923
00:56:19.288 --> 00:56:22.388
that chromatin accessibility marker continues to be there in the

924
00:56:22.428 --> 00:56:26.308
tissue. And when that tissue is further exposed in the future to oncogenic

925
00:56:26.328 --> 00:56:26.988
mutations,

926
00:56:27.938 --> 00:56:31.888
that can lead to an augmented secondary response with tumorigenesis.

927
00:56:31.928 --> 00:56:35.588
So I think epigenetic memory can be a convergent pathway by which

928
00:56:35.628 --> 00:56:39.388
multiple lifestyle factors can predispose individuals to future

929
00:56:39.448 --> 00:56:40.108
cancer risk.

930
00:56:41.988 --> 00:56:43.568
So finally, I want to turn to the last

931
00:56:44.448 --> 00:56:47.808
part of the presentation, which is around the top of the pyramid, the

932
00:56:47.868 --> 00:56:50.568
apex, really that prevention setting.

933
00:56:50.628 --> 00:56:54.468
Because ultimately this early onset situation is something that we want to get to

934
00:56:54.508 --> 00:56:58.448
the bottom of because we want to have some actionable solutions in the near term

935
00:56:58.508 --> 00:57:01.888
for prevention. And that's really the apex of the pyramid and where

936
00:57:01.908 --> 00:57:03.848
the

937
00:57:04.808 --> 00:57:08.608
field needs to go to really make progress in this really difficult

938
00:57:08.618 --> 00:57:09.068
problem.

939
00:57:10.068 --> 00:57:12.588
So how do we advance causality to prevention?

940
00:57:12.628 --> 00:57:16.178
And I won't have time to go into detail with any of these specific

941
00:57:16.208 --> 00:57:18.837
interventions, but I want to really highlight the fact that

942
00:57:19.648 --> 00:57:23.148
among these different pathways, we know that there are central nodes.

943
00:57:24.028 --> 00:57:25.688
We know inflammation is a central node.

944
00:57:25.748 --> 00:57:28.548
Obesity is a node, dysbiosis is a node.

945
00:57:28.588 --> 00:57:32.208
They all represent opportunities for us to do something about this problem.

946
00:57:32.968 --> 00:57:36.508
For inflammation, for example, we know there are anti-inflammatory agents like

947
00:57:36.608 --> 00:57:39.868
aspirin, and there's a very strong evidence base supporting the fact that aspirin

948
00:57:39.888 --> 00:57:43.828
reduces colorectal cancer risk. And certainly, that represents a very viable option

949
00:57:43.868 --> 00:57:47.528
in a young population for whom risk factors are

950
00:57:47.568 --> 00:57:51.468
there for inflammation and chronic development of

951
00:57:51.728 --> 00:57:52.768
polyps and cancer.

952
00:57:53.768 --> 00:57:56.308
But they're also a population for which

953
00:57:57.208 --> 00:57:59.808
potential side effects of aspirin are much lower.

954
00:58:00.688 --> 00:58:04.598
In addition, we know that they're highly effective agents against obesity and

955
00:58:04.628 --> 00:58:07.997
type 2 diabetes that have also been discussed widely in this meeting and in other

956
00:58:08.008 --> 00:58:11.868
meetings. And so GLP-1 receptor agonists may represent a potential

957
00:58:11.888 --> 00:58:12.898
preventive intervention.

958
00:58:13.878 --> 00:58:17.388
And then finally, we know there are ways potentially to modulate the gut

959
00:58:17.408 --> 00:58:20.868
microbiome through dietary interventions, fiber supplementation, et cetera.

960
00:58:20.988 --> 00:58:23.688
So these are all potential options for prevention.

961
00:58:24.968 --> 00:58:28.748
So one of these options is something we're pursuing within Team Prospect,

962
00:58:28.848 --> 00:58:31.968
looking at highly effective obesity agents.

963
00:58:32.028 --> 00:58:35.848
So in a cohort of adults between the ages of 40 to 49 with a history of

964
00:58:35.908 --> 00:58:38.388
adenoma that we see at Mass General Hospital,

965
00:58:39.328 --> 00:58:42.968
we are currently enrolling patients in a trial, a single-arm trial, where we're

966
00:58:42.978 --> 00:58:44.208
treating them with tirzepatide,

967
00:58:45.668 --> 00:58:49.448
which is a GLP-1 GIP agonist. And at baseline, we're doing a

968
00:58:49.468 --> 00:58:53.188
flexible sigmoidoscopy, collecting tissue samples, as well as a variety of

969
00:58:53.228 --> 00:58:56.388
biosamples like blood, urine, and stool.

970
00:58:56.468 --> 00:59:00.388
Following them over time serially with a checkout visit at

971
00:59:00.448 --> 00:59:01.038
six months,

972
00:59:01.868 --> 00:59:05.697
which also includes a flexible sigmoidoscopy in which we're using tissue biopsies,

973
00:59:05.748 --> 00:59:09.688
et cetera. And this will give us some correlative biomarkers to understand, are

974
00:59:09.708 --> 00:59:13.428
there epigenetic markers that change with reversal of

975
00:59:13.468 --> 00:59:17.068
obesity overweight? Are there also cancer-specific

976
00:59:17.148 --> 00:59:20.968
biomarkers that we can look at? And so this study is being led at MGH

977
00:59:21.108 --> 00:59:24.368
by David Drew and myself, and we're hopeful that we're going to have some results

978
00:59:24.378 --> 00:59:26.468
to report out next year.

979
00:59:27.548 --> 00:59:30.988
Finally, I do want to note that there's the question about do we need to even

980
00:59:31.048 --> 00:59:34.508
intervene earlier? And as Dr. Alexandrov will talk about, if some of these

981
00:59:34.548 --> 00:59:38.488
lifestyle factors and some of these metabolic risk factors or microbiome factors

982
00:59:38.528 --> 00:59:42.028
really do happen really early in life, how do we then intervene?

983
00:59:42.148 --> 00:59:45.828
Because it's very difficult to imagine a scenario where we would repurpose

984
00:59:45.848 --> 00:59:48.948
pharmacological agents for infants or for pregnant mothers.

985
00:59:49.498 --> 00:59:53.048
So that's where we have to really think about new ways or new modalities of

986
00:59:53.068 --> 00:59:56.998
implementation science, and policy changes, where maybe we can

987
00:59:57.028 --> 01:00:00.718
try to alter some of these obesogenic exposures

988
01:00:01.108 --> 01:00:04.708
through policy changes, where we can maybe alter our food environment to eliminate

989
01:00:04.768 --> 01:00:08.688
some of these things from a national perspective and eliminate some of the

990
01:00:08.708 --> 01:00:11.128
disparities that we see in early-onset cancer risk, which Dr.

991
01:00:11.368 --> 01:00:12.758
Sung also nicely mentioned.

992
01:00:14.488 --> 01:00:18.098
So in summary, I hope we've been able to show you how early-onset colorectal

993
01:00:18.128 --> 01:00:21.188
cancer is an area in which we've made some progress.

994
01:00:21.268 --> 01:00:24.968
We're understanding more about it, and we're starting to develop some opportunities

995
01:00:24.988 --> 01:00:27.828
for prevention, which I think is so critically needed in the field.

996
01:00:28.608 --> 01:00:31.248
It also requires us to have a life course framework.

997
01:00:32.188 --> 01:00:36.048
We need to also be able to develop mechanistic models using both mice

998
01:00:36.228 --> 01:00:40.088
and also human samples to really advance correlation to causality, because clinical

999
01:00:40.188 --> 01:00:42.568
trial data is going to be very difficult to come by.

1000
01:00:43.328 --> 01:00:47.048
And ultimately, causality can be advanced to prevention

1001
01:00:47.168 --> 01:00:50.912
through proof-of-principle human trials.So I want to

1002
01:00:50.922 --> 01:00:54.822
acknowledge the folks in my group at MGH who've

1003
01:00:54.852 --> 01:00:56.892
led a lot of the data that I presented here today.

1004
01:00:56.932 --> 01:01:00.872
Certainly, our co-investigators on Team Prospect, just a remarkably

1005
01:01:00.882 --> 01:01:04.772
dedicated team of investigators, in particular Ian Cowell, my co-lead

1006
01:01:04.832 --> 01:01:08.252
of this team, as well as our really dedicated patient advocates.

1007
01:01:08.272 --> 01:01:12.172
And I can't emphasize enough how our patient advocates have been so

1008
01:01:12.292 --> 01:01:15.752
vital to this program. They've been with us every step of the way in both

1009
01:01:15.792 --> 01:01:19.482
informing the design of our research, but also inspiring us to really

1010
01:01:19.482 --> 01:01:20.942
address this challenging problem.

1011
01:01:21.632 --> 01:01:24.752
The participants of all of our studies, we want to acknowledge our funders, and

1012
01:01:24.792 --> 01:01:27.992
also just want to mention that a lot of these topics and a lot of these issues

1013
01:01:28.032 --> 01:01:31.852
around prevention and how we prevent cancers are areas that we hope to

1014
01:01:31.892 --> 01:01:35.522
cover at a cancer prevention research conference that we're having

1015
01:01:36.272 --> 01:01:38.912
in June, that I have the privilege of co-chairing.

1016
01:01:38.992 --> 01:01:42.472
So if you're interested in attending that conference, the QR code is there.

1017
01:01:44.372 --> 01:01:46.272
So with that, I thank you for your attention.

1018
01:01:46.342 --> 01:01:50.132
And now I do want to take the opportunity to introduce

1019
01:01:50.252 --> 01:01:53.692
our next speaker. We're very happy to present Dr.

1020
01:01:53.992 --> 01:01:57.792
Ludmil Alexandrov from University of California,

1021
01:01:57.892 --> 01:01:59.452
San Diego. He's a professor

1022
01:02:00.292 --> 01:02:04.242
of molecular medicine, and he will discuss early life mutagenesis and

1023
01:02:04.272 --> 01:02:06.872
the rise of early onset cancer. Thank you for your attention.

1024
01:02:14.342 --> 01:02:17.912
Good morning, everyone. I'm delighted to be here and to tell you more

1025
01:02:17.952 --> 01:02:21.312
about our work on early onset colorectal cancer, and

1026
01:02:21.372 --> 01:02:24.672
specifically on our work on how early life

1027
01:02:24.712 --> 01:02:28.412
mutagenesis can be contributing to early onset colorectal cancer.

1028
01:02:28.472 --> 01:02:30.532
Now, most talks end with a summary.

1029
01:02:30.812 --> 01:02:34.372
My talk is going to actually end with a hypothesis, and I really hope that this

1030
01:02:34.412 --> 01:02:37.692
hypothesis will excite at least some in the audience.

1031
01:02:38.692 --> 01:02:40.612
Oh, and of course, these are my disclosures.

1032
01:02:40.732 --> 01:02:43.392
Please keep them in mind while I'm presenting.

1033
01:02:44.172 --> 01:02:47.752
So I'm going to start with an overview of somatic mutations, mutational

1034
01:02:47.852 --> 01:02:50.712
signatures, and human cancer. We have known for

1035
01:02:51.892 --> 01:02:55.082
quite a while that somatic mutations accumulate daily.

1036
01:02:55.502 --> 01:02:59.432
They accumulate in every single cell of the body, and they can accumulate

1037
01:02:59.472 --> 01:03:03.332
from lifestyle choices, they can accumulate from failure of

1038
01:03:03.372 --> 01:03:07.261
cellular mechanisms, and also they can accumulate just because the cell exists,

1039
01:03:07.402 --> 01:03:09.732
the cell divides, the cell generates energy.

1040
01:03:10.032 --> 01:03:13.752
So somatic mutations and their accumulation are just part of daily life.

1041
01:03:14.552 --> 01:03:18.452
Now, we have known also for maybe four or five decades that cancer

1042
01:03:18.512 --> 01:03:20.712
risk is strongly affected by mutagenesis.

1043
01:03:21.162 --> 01:03:24.792
The more mutations one accumulates, the higher the risk for developing

1044
01:03:24.832 --> 01:03:28.732
cancer. And this is perhaps best exemplified by tobacco smoking, which

1045
01:03:28.772 --> 01:03:32.432
mutates multiple organs of the human body, perhaps most notably the

1046
01:03:32.492 --> 01:03:36.372
lung. And again, if we look at lung squamous cell carcinoma,

1047
01:03:36.512 --> 01:03:40.392
one type of lung cancer, only one patient with this cancer

1048
01:03:40.412 --> 01:03:43.972
type will report being a never smoker, while the remaining 104

1049
01:03:43.992 --> 01:03:46.332
patients will report being smokers.

1050
01:03:46.612 --> 01:03:49.782
So you have something that increases the mutational burden, generates many

1051
01:03:49.782 --> 01:03:53.052
mutations, and substantially affects cancer risk.

1052
01:03:53.712 --> 01:03:57.632
So perhaps 10 or 15 years ago, the question came,

1053
01:03:57.912 --> 01:04:01.402
if we look at cancer genomes, if we look at the next-generation

1054
01:04:01.472 --> 01:04:05.312
sequencing data from cancer genomes, can we say what is

1055
01:04:05.372 --> 01:04:09.152
generating these mutations? Can we figure out the mutational processes causing

1056
01:04:09.252 --> 01:04:13.212
mutations and the mutational causes of cancer using

1057
01:04:13.512 --> 01:04:17.212
these mutational processes? And essentially, this became known as mutational

1058
01:04:17.272 --> 01:04:21.012
signature analysis, a simple machine learning approach that you apply to

1059
01:04:21.032 --> 01:04:22.752
next-generation sequencing data.

1060
01:04:23.102 --> 01:04:26.092
And I just want to give you some examples, some poster child examples.

1061
01:04:26.172 --> 01:04:29.352
So when we think about skin cancer, we usually think about

1062
01:04:29.772 --> 01:04:33.692
ultraviolet light exposure, because majority of skin cancers are caused

1063
01:04:33.732 --> 01:04:35.132
by UV light exposure.

1064
01:04:36.052 --> 01:04:40.002
And indeed, UV light exposure has a very characteristic pattern of mutations.

1065
01:04:40.072 --> 01:04:43.542
You can see it here, predominantly C to T mutations in a very

1066
01:04:43.912 --> 01:04:47.852
specific context. That context is dipymidines, very well

1067
01:04:47.912 --> 01:04:50.472
matching the biophysical properties of UV light.

1068
01:04:50.912 --> 01:04:54.832
So if we look at skin, healthy skin, we are going to see

1069
01:04:54.852 --> 01:04:56.932
this UV light exposure

1070
01:04:57.772 --> 01:05:00.392
generating many mutations across these healthy skin

1071
01:05:01.632 --> 01:05:05.472
genomes. But also, if we look at the genomes of melanomas,

1072
01:05:05.552 --> 01:05:08.632
we're going to see very high levels of this mutational signature.

1073
01:05:09.272 --> 01:05:12.932
Now, in lung cancer, again, most of the time, we associate lung

1074
01:05:12.992 --> 01:05:16.872
cancer with tobacco smoking, and indeed, about 80% of all types

1075
01:05:16.912 --> 01:05:19.352
of lung cancer are caused by tobacco smoking.

1076
01:05:19.372 --> 01:05:22.592
And when we look at the genomes of these lung cancer patients, we're going to see

1077
01:05:22.652 --> 01:05:26.272
again another characteristic pattern of mutation, also Signature

1078
01:05:26.632 --> 01:05:30.292
4, generating predominantly blue mutations and some gray mutations

1079
01:05:30.352 --> 01:05:34.012
here, and leaving its mutagenic pattern just because a

1080
01:05:34.032 --> 01:05:37.702
person smokes. Now again, the mutational

1081
01:05:37.732 --> 01:05:39.262
signatures not only allow us to

1082
01:05:40.132 --> 01:05:43.772
find an exposure, but they allow us to evaluate how an

1083
01:05:43.812 --> 01:05:45.992
exposure is going to mutate the normal tissue.

1084
01:05:46.372 --> 01:05:50.172
So if we have a person who is smoking a pack of cigarettes per day for a

1085
01:05:50.192 --> 01:05:53.852
year, on average, every single cell of their lung tissues is going to

1086
01:05:53.892 --> 01:05:57.722
accumulate about 150 mutations, their larynx 97

1087
01:05:57.792 --> 01:06:01.202
mutations, and you can see the numbers for the other parts of their

1088
01:06:01.292 --> 01:06:05.032
body. And this mutational increase very nicely tracks with the risk

1089
01:06:06.432 --> 01:06:10.252
that tobacco smoking confers for developing cancer in these different

1090
01:06:10.352 --> 01:06:14.202
organs. Now, over the last 10 or 15 years,

1091
01:06:14.732 --> 01:06:18.632
there has been many studies on identifying the repertoire of mutational

1092
01:06:18.732 --> 01:06:22.412
signatures, and we and others have mapped over 100 mutational

1093
01:06:22.472 --> 01:06:24.712
signatures across the spectrum of human cancers.

1094
01:06:25.172 --> 01:06:27.392
You have processes happening within the cells.

1095
01:06:27.972 --> 01:06:31.952
You have processes that are happening due to treatment,

1096
01:06:32.132 --> 01:06:34.092
whether chemotherapy or other treatment.

1097
01:06:34.492 --> 01:06:38.472
And we also have processes that are due to environmental exposures or

1098
01:06:38.512 --> 01:06:41.872
exogenous mutagens. So there is quite a plethora of different

1099
01:06:41.932 --> 01:06:45.892
exposures, and from the over 100 mutational signatures that we have

1100
01:06:45.972 --> 01:06:49.772
identified, more than half we do not know what's their

1101
01:06:49.852 --> 01:06:53.816
cause.Now, one signature that's specifically important for this

1102
01:06:53.856 --> 01:06:55.956
talk is the signature of colibactin.

1103
01:06:56.576 --> 01:06:59.696
And colibactin, if you're not familiar with that, it's a

1104
01:06:59.736 --> 01:07:03.616
genotoxin that's being produced by certain bacteria, and more

1105
01:07:03.676 --> 01:07:05.576
specifically, by certain types of E.

1106
01:07:05.656 --> 01:07:08.476
coli and other bacteria that carry the pks locus.

1107
01:07:09.096 --> 01:07:12.876
And from an experimental perspective, this mutational signature was

1108
01:07:12.936 --> 01:07:13.636
first

1109
01:07:14.496 --> 01:07:17.076
described by Hans Clevers in a very elegant work

1110
01:07:17.676 --> 01:07:20.116
where Hans and his team

1111
01:07:21.056 --> 01:07:24.636
grew intestinal organoids, some with the pks positive

1112
01:07:24.696 --> 01:07:27.776
bacteria, and some without the pks positive bacteria.

1113
01:07:28.106 --> 01:07:31.716
And then they clonally expanded them, they sequenced them, and they found this very

1114
01:07:31.756 --> 01:07:35.696
nice mutational signature, which they called the signature of pks

1115
01:07:36.756 --> 01:07:40.276
positivity. And then at the same time, many studies of human

1116
01:07:40.376 --> 01:07:44.316
cancers and normal tissues were analyzing cancer genomes

1117
01:07:44.516 --> 01:07:48.356
or normal colorectal tissues, and they found Signature 88.

1118
01:07:48.796 --> 01:07:52.376
And again, you can see that the patterns of this Signature 88 matches almost

1119
01:07:52.496 --> 01:07:56.036
perfectly the pattern of the experimental pks signature.

1120
01:07:56.376 --> 01:08:00.356
And indeed, Signature 88 became the mutational signature of colibactin,

1121
01:08:00.906 --> 01:08:04.336
and in addition to that, there is an additional insertion and deletion

1122
01:08:04.436 --> 01:08:08.136
signature. So mutational signatures allow us to

1123
01:08:08.156 --> 01:08:12.076
understand the processes that cause mutations and about maybe now

1124
01:08:12.136 --> 01:08:15.656
10 years ago, the field of genomic epidemiology

1125
01:08:15.836 --> 01:08:19.516
started utilizing them to understand the causes of

1126
01:08:19.556 --> 01:08:19.996
cancer.

1127
01:08:20.876 --> 01:08:24.076
And we were very lucky in 2017 to be funded by

1128
01:08:24.736 --> 01:08:28.596
Cancer Research UK as part of the Mutographs Grand Challenge to

1129
01:08:28.637 --> 01:08:32.446
try and understand why different countries around the world have

1130
01:08:32.476 --> 01:08:35.837
different risks for developing cancer. And the idea was simple.

1131
01:08:35.876 --> 01:08:39.266
We're going to go around the world, we're going to sequence tumors, and we're going

1132
01:08:39.276 --> 01:08:43.087
to see whether they have different mutational signatures and whether we can

1133
01:08:43.137 --> 01:08:46.776
explain the cancer risk based on mutational

1134
01:08:46.816 --> 01:08:50.556
signatures. And one of those cancer types was colorectal

1135
01:08:50.596 --> 01:08:53.936
cancer. And again, the previous two talks very nicely

1136
01:08:53.996 --> 01:08:57.816
emphasized that colorectal cancer has been increasing in young adults

1137
01:08:58.056 --> 01:09:02.036
and has been decreasing in older generations, but just to keep in mind, there

1138
01:09:02.056 --> 01:09:05.686
is also differences of colorectal cancer risk around the world,

1139
01:09:06.337 --> 01:09:10.137
with some countries having substantially higher risk for developing colorectal

1140
01:09:10.177 --> 01:09:14.016
cancer than others. And when we were conducting our study, our original

1141
01:09:14.056 --> 01:09:17.896
objective was to investigate that, to understand why certain countries

1142
01:09:17.936 --> 01:09:21.866
have a high risk for colorectal cancer and certain countries have a lower risk for

1143
01:09:21.936 --> 01:09:25.816
colorectal cancer. At the same time, the emergence of early

1144
01:09:25.856 --> 01:09:29.566
onset colorectal cancer was becoming more and more prominent or more than a

1145
01:09:29.576 --> 01:09:31.337
twofold increase, as we heard before.

1146
01:09:31.976 --> 01:09:35.757
It was mapped as a global phenomenon with

1147
01:09:35.816 --> 01:09:39.696
over 27 countries reporting the increase of early onset colorectal

1148
01:09:39.736 --> 01:09:43.677
cancers. And again, there were not really any known

1149
01:09:43.736 --> 01:09:47.476
risk factors that were described except perhaps the ones that Andy was

1150
01:09:47.536 --> 01:09:48.856
mentioning just a moment ago.

1151
01:09:49.776 --> 01:09:53.556
And it is becoming the leading cause of death among young

1152
01:09:53.616 --> 01:09:57.276
adults. And again, as it was emphasized in some of the previous talks, this was

1153
01:09:57.336 --> 01:10:01.256
very highly featured in the general media with many different

1154
01:10:01.276 --> 01:10:01.896
headlines

1155
01:10:03.076 --> 01:10:06.716
talking about early onset cases and specifically early onset colorectal

1156
01:10:06.756 --> 01:10:10.336
cancer. Now, I should say that when we started our study,

1157
01:10:10.596 --> 01:10:13.556
our focus was actually to understand geographic differences.

1158
01:10:13.636 --> 01:10:17.436
We wanted to understand why some countries have more cancers than others.

1159
01:10:17.976 --> 01:10:21.796
And indeed, we collected about 1,000 colorectal cancers, all of

1160
01:10:21.836 --> 01:10:25.516
them treatment-naïve, and we collected them from 11 countries with

1161
01:10:25.536 --> 01:10:29.496
different risks for cancer. And you can see there's countries with high risk

1162
01:10:29.516 --> 01:10:32.896
for cancer, such as Japan, which has ASR, or a

1163
01:10:32.976 --> 01:10:36.516
standardized risk over 35, and there are countries with low risk for

1164
01:10:36.536 --> 01:10:39.556
developing cancer, such as Iran and Thailand.

1165
01:10:39.996 --> 01:10:43.706
And for each of those tumors, we did whole genome sequencing of the tumor and

1166
01:10:43.756 --> 01:10:46.176
normal, and then we derived somatic mutations.

1167
01:10:46.756 --> 01:10:50.736
Now, just because early onset cases were increasing so much, we

1168
01:10:51.496 --> 01:10:55.436
were able to capture over 130 early onset colorectal

1169
01:10:55.476 --> 01:10:59.416
cancers as part of that cohort. And indeed, we were able to capture early

1170
01:10:59.436 --> 01:11:03.285
onset cases both in the proximal tumor, in the proximal colon,

1171
01:11:03.396 --> 01:11:07.135
distant colon, and in the rectum, and with different percentages.

1172
01:11:07.436 --> 01:11:11.396
But again, quite the representative view of early onset cases and late

1173
01:11:11.436 --> 01:11:12.356
onset cases.

1174
01:11:13.576 --> 01:11:13.676
Now,

1175
01:11:14.496 --> 01:11:17.996
there is many ways to show you colorectal cancer, but I wanted to do it in probably

1176
01:11:18.016 --> 01:11:21.576
the most genomics way one can do, and that's by looking at

1177
01:11:21.616 --> 01:11:22.296
mutations.

1178
01:11:24.196 --> 01:11:28.136
And what you can see here on this y-axis is the single point mutations or the

1179
01:11:28.196 --> 01:11:32.036
single base substitutions, and this is log scale, so you have 10,000,

1180
01:11:32.096 --> 01:11:35.896
100,000, a million mutations. On this x-axis, you can

1181
01:11:35.936 --> 01:11:39.796
see what percentage of the genome is altered, so how genomically unstable

1182
01:11:39.836 --> 01:11:43.696
is colorectal cancer. And here you can see the insertions and deletions, how

1183
01:11:43.716 --> 01:11:46.686
many small base pairs are deleted in colorectal cancer.

1184
01:11:47.516 --> 01:11:51.016
And the first type of colorectal cancer, molecular subtype of colorectal cancer, is

1185
01:11:51.056 --> 01:11:52.996
the microsatellite stable tumors.

1186
01:11:53.416 --> 01:11:56.956
These are tumors that there is no defects in any known DNA repair

1187
01:11:57.056 --> 01:12:00.596
mechanisms, and they have on average about maybe 10,000

1188
01:12:00.636 --> 01:12:04.296
mutations, and they have about 1,000 to 2,000

1189
01:12:04.496 --> 01:12:08.216
insertions and deletions. Now, as you can see, their genomes could be stable

1190
01:12:08.616 --> 01:12:11.336
or very unstable. They're from the full spectrum.

1191
01:12:11.936 --> 01:12:15.486
And about 800 of the 1,000 samples were microsatellite

1192
01:12:15.536 --> 01:12:19.276
stable. The second category is microsatellite unstable

1193
01:12:19.376 --> 01:12:22.956
tumors, and again, these are about 150 of the

1194
01:12:23.116 --> 01:12:26.656
1,000 tumors. And now you see tumors that have substantially more

1195
01:12:26.676 --> 01:12:30.496
mutations, an order of magnitude more, and about two orders of

1196
01:12:30.576 --> 01:12:32.716
magnitude more insertions and deletions.

1197
01:12:33.056 --> 01:12:36.756
So the failure of mismatch repair in these tumors have generated a very different

1198
01:12:36.816 --> 01:12:37.856
molecular profile.

1199
01:12:40.336 --> 01:12:44.096
One can obviously validate this clinically with digital droplet PCR or

1200
01:12:44.156 --> 01:12:47.816
immunohistochemistry, and all the ones here have been validated.

1201
01:12:48.236 --> 01:12:51.956
And there is also other ones such as the polymerase epsilon and polymerase delta.

1202
01:12:52.036 --> 01:12:54.236
Now, these tumors have millions of mutations,

1203
01:12:55.336 --> 01:12:58.016
and they have very stable genomes.

1204
01:12:58.486 --> 01:13:00.136
And there are even more rare subtypes.

1205
01:13:00.176 --> 01:13:03.336
You have the MUTYH, the NTH1, the OGG1.

1206
01:13:03.696 --> 01:13:06.136
We had seven patients with BRCA2 mutations.

1207
01:13:06.526 --> 01:13:10.456
So again, out of 1,000 patients, less than 1%

1208
01:13:10.516 --> 01:13:14.086
having different types of DNA repair defects and exhibiting

1209
01:13:14.116 --> 01:13:17.792
different molecular phenotypes.One

1210
01:13:18.332 --> 01:13:21.092
thing that we were surprised to see is

1211
01:13:21.112 --> 01:13:25.092
signatures of chemotherapy. About two samples that

1212
01:13:25.112 --> 01:13:28.812
we examined had chemotherapy signatures, and again, our cohort was

1213
01:13:28.822 --> 01:13:32.272
supposed to be a chemotherapy-naive cohort.

1214
01:13:32.332 --> 01:13:34.632
We were not supposed to have any treatment.

1215
01:13:35.092 --> 01:13:38.552
And again, when we went and looked at the data, it turned out that these people had

1216
01:13:38.792 --> 01:13:42.232
prior cancers. One of them had a prior cancer in childhood.

1217
01:13:42.312 --> 01:13:45.712
That person was treated, and the treatment left this

1218
01:13:45.832 --> 01:13:47.172
mutational imprint,

1219
01:13:48.182 --> 01:13:51.832
and we can detect it later within their secondary tumor, which was colorectal

1220
01:13:51.892 --> 01:13:55.772
cancer. So the fact that you have an exposure earlier in life, you can

1221
01:13:55.832 --> 01:13:58.272
keep seeing these mutations later in life.

1222
01:13:59.332 --> 01:14:02.472
Now, as you can imagine, some of these categories are very small.

1223
01:14:02.612 --> 01:14:04.372
You have just a few samples in them.

1224
01:14:04.852 --> 01:14:08.792
So we reported them, and essentially we reported their rates,

1225
01:14:08.922 --> 01:14:12.472
and we left them aside because they have very different molecular profiles.

1226
01:14:13.172 --> 01:14:15.992
We did a deep dive on the microsatellite unstable tumors.

1227
01:14:16.472 --> 01:14:19.292
Again, they have about an order of magnitude more mutations.

1228
01:14:19.412 --> 01:14:19.492
So

1229
01:14:20.532 --> 01:14:24.352
failure of DNA repair really generates many mutations,

1230
01:14:24.832 --> 01:14:28.132
and we weren't able to find anything statistically significant.

1231
01:14:29.072 --> 01:14:32.592
So again, we have reported that, but we have put them aside.

1232
01:14:32.692 --> 01:14:36.492
And our main results and the main focus has been on the microsatellite stable

1233
01:14:36.512 --> 01:14:40.312
tumors, because these are the tumors where we know there is no failure of DNA

1234
01:14:40.372 --> 01:14:43.532
repair and where we can really evaluate different

1235
01:14:43.572 --> 01:14:45.242
environmental exposures.

1236
01:14:46.212 --> 01:14:46.772
Now,

1237
01:14:47.832 --> 01:14:51.792
there we did the mutational signature analysis, and we found a large

1238
01:14:51.852 --> 01:14:55.712
number of different signatures. And I'm not going to tell you all

1239
01:14:55.732 --> 01:14:59.392
the details. I'm just going to tell you that we found the usual suspects, the

1240
01:14:59.432 --> 01:15:02.892
clock-like signatures that are due to aging, the APOBEC signatures

1241
01:15:03.352 --> 01:15:06.932
due to deaminases, reactive oxygen species,

1242
01:15:07.492 --> 01:15:11.402
colibactin, which is going to become important in just a moment, and

1243
01:15:11.432 --> 01:15:14.972
then many signatures that have unknown etiologies, many

1244
01:15:15.072 --> 01:15:18.592
signatures that we do not know what is causing

1245
01:15:18.892 --> 01:15:19.192
them.

1246
01:15:20.612 --> 01:15:22.572
And again, this is just the single point mutations.

1247
01:15:22.652 --> 01:15:26.412
We did mutational signature analysis across all different types

1248
01:15:26.532 --> 01:15:30.372
of somatic mutations. So the first question that we wanted to

1249
01:15:30.432 --> 01:15:32.572
answer is, are there differences between countries?

1250
01:15:32.652 --> 01:15:36.532
This is the original question we started with, and we wanted to understand whether

1251
01:15:36.572 --> 01:15:40.072
we can observe any differences. And again, one needs to do this

1252
01:15:40.132 --> 01:15:43.772
carefully. We did one versus all comparison while adjusting by age,

1253
01:15:44.052 --> 01:15:47.692
sex, tumor subtype, and purity, and we can see clear differences.

1254
01:15:48.092 --> 01:15:51.752
So when one compares the Russian Federation to all other countries, you can see

1255
01:15:51.772 --> 01:15:55.332
enrichment of APOBEC signatures and novel signatures of unknown

1256
01:15:55.352 --> 01:15:58.852
etiology. Argentina, we see three novel

1257
01:15:58.892 --> 01:16:02.572
signatures or three signatures of unknown etiologies being enriched there.

1258
01:16:02.632 --> 01:16:05.412
In Brazil, one signature being enriched.

1259
01:16:05.452 --> 01:16:09.132
In Colombia, three signatures being enriched and one being

1260
01:16:09.172 --> 01:16:12.032
depleted, again, all of them of unknown etiologies.

1261
01:16:12.412 --> 01:16:15.892
And in Thailand, one signature that's being depleted.

1262
01:16:16.832 --> 01:16:19.032
And you can see how this looks on a map.

1263
01:16:19.072 --> 01:16:22.932
You can see Signature F, which we do not know what causes it, and you see that

1264
01:16:22.972 --> 01:16:25.172
it's very highly prevalent in Colombia.

1265
01:16:25.212 --> 01:16:28.932
We find it all over the world, but the prevalence is highest

1266
01:16:29.112 --> 01:16:30.572
in Colombia in this specific case.

1267
01:16:31.012 --> 01:16:34.752
And again, you can see here SBS89 and the signatures that

1268
01:16:34.812 --> 01:16:38.742
usually strongly correlate with it, the IDG and BBS8, very

1269
01:16:39.112 --> 01:16:42.522
common in Argentina. Again, we see it in the rest of the world, but

1270
01:16:42.552 --> 01:16:46.502
we do not know what its etiology is.

1271
01:16:46.552 --> 01:16:49.012
So we were seeing these many signatures.

1272
01:16:49.132 --> 01:16:53.072
We were discovering these signatures that may even explain the difference in cancer

1273
01:16:53.132 --> 01:16:55.632
risk, but we could not know their causality.

1274
01:16:55.641 --> 01:16:58.092
We didn't know their underlying mechanisms.

1275
01:16:58.112 --> 01:17:01.892
And as you can imagine, this could be a deeply frustrating exercise because you

1276
01:17:01.932 --> 01:17:05.912
really want to understand what causes the signatures if you want to prevent cancer.

1277
01:17:06.592 --> 01:17:10.052
And I'm very delighted to say that starting in 10 days,

1278
01:17:10.752 --> 01:17:14.212
we have been funded for a cancer grant challenge specifically for that, to be able

1279
01:17:14.232 --> 01:17:18.132
to investigate the mechanisms of these mutational signatures and being

1280
01:17:18.372 --> 01:17:21.872
able to understand what underlies their mechanisms.

1281
01:17:21.902 --> 01:17:25.692
And we're hoping to be able to report more interesting details

1282
01:17:25.752 --> 01:17:28.472
versus we have signatures of unknown etiology.

1283
01:17:29.232 --> 01:17:32.372
Rather, we want to be able to report this is a signature, this is what causes these

1284
01:17:32.432 --> 01:17:36.232
signatures, and ideally, this is the way we can prevent this signature.

1285
01:17:36.992 --> 01:17:39.712
Now, this was a comparison between countries.

1286
01:17:39.772 --> 01:17:43.732
What about the early onset cases? And there we had probably the most interesting

1287
01:17:43.792 --> 01:17:47.612
result in our analysis. When we separated our case

1288
01:17:47.632 --> 01:17:51.152
based on the age of people, we can see a very high

1289
01:17:51.192 --> 01:17:54.022
enrichment for at least three mutational signatures,

1290
01:17:54.572 --> 01:17:58.032
SBS88 and ID18, both of them due to

1291
01:17:58.072 --> 01:18:01.822
colibactin. One is the indel signature, the other one is a substitution signature,

1292
01:18:02.272 --> 01:18:05.622
and SBS89, which is a signature of unknown etiology.

1293
01:18:06.122 --> 01:18:09.902
And to give you an idea, the colibactin mutational signature is found in about

1294
01:18:10.092 --> 01:18:13.732
50% of people under the age of 40 and about 16% to

1295
01:18:13.752 --> 01:18:17.492
17% of people over the age of 70. So we're talking

1296
01:18:17.552 --> 01:18:21.192
about a threefold difference between these different age groups.

1297
01:18:21.672 --> 01:18:23.552
So that was quite the striking result.

1298
01:18:24.062 --> 01:18:27.552
And again, we knew the mechanism of this signature, which meant we can look in more

1299
01:18:27.632 --> 01:18:31.162
details in this signature. And the first question we ask is,

1300
01:18:31.292 --> 01:18:34.952
well, if this is due to pks positive bacteria, do we see

1301
01:18:34.992 --> 01:18:38.692
colonization of that bacteria? And again, you can see a

1302
01:18:38.752 --> 01:18:42.232
sample here. This is one patient that has the pks positive

1303
01:18:42.252 --> 01:18:45.992
signature. And also we can look at the sequencing data, and we can see that there

1304
01:18:46.012 --> 01:18:49.372
is pks colonization. And there is another patient here.

1305
01:18:49.432 --> 01:18:50.752
Again, it will have the

1306
01:18:52.352 --> 01:18:56.232
colibactin mutational signatures, but it has absolutely no pks

1307
01:18:56.352 --> 01:19:00.242
reads. And you can do the same analysis across the complete cohort, and what

1308
01:19:00.272 --> 01:19:02.952
we saw is that there was no associations of us seeing

1309
01:19:03.052 --> 01:19:06.452
colonization and us seeing the presence of a

1310
01:19:06.492 --> 01:19:10.232
mutational signature. And that was true across the complete cohort, and that was

1311
01:19:10.312 --> 01:19:13.112
also true across all different age groups.

1312
01:19:13.622 --> 01:19:17.542
And again, that could make sense. You do not need to have colonization in this

1313
01:19:17.612 --> 01:19:21.492
very moment. You could have had a past exposure to this genotoxic

1314
01:19:21.572 --> 01:19:23.312
bacteria that generates the mutations.

1315
01:19:24.062 --> 01:19:26.352
And then the question came, when was that exposure?

1316
01:19:26.552 --> 01:19:30.372
Can we go back in time? When were these people exposed to this

1317
01:19:30.452 --> 01:19:34.360
specific colibactin signature?So the first thing we did is to time it

1318
01:19:34.400 --> 01:19:36.180
from a cancer evolution perspective.

1319
01:19:36.500 --> 01:19:39.800
I'm not going to go to the way the cancer evolution

1320
01:19:40.200 --> 01:19:43.440
timing and modeling works, but the results were very, very

1321
01:19:43.780 --> 01:19:47.620
conclusive. The colibactin signatures were some of the earliest

1322
01:19:47.640 --> 01:19:51.300
processes in cancer evolution that were happening very

1323
01:19:51.380 --> 01:19:53.660
early as the cancer was starting to develop.

1324
01:19:54.180 --> 01:19:57.799
Now, that doesn't tell us the age of the person when that tumor

1325
01:19:57.840 --> 01:20:01.520
develops, but it tells us it's one of the earliest processes in cancer.

1326
01:20:02.340 --> 01:20:05.740
But we really wanted to get to that question, at what age do these people get

1327
01:20:05.760 --> 01:20:09.380
exposed? And again, to do that, one needs to do a bit of

1328
01:20:09.720 --> 01:20:13.620
fancy molecular archeology. And the way one does that

1329
01:20:13.820 --> 01:20:17.640
is to take normal colorectal crypts from a cancer patient.

1330
01:20:17.740 --> 01:20:21.620
Here you see 15 of them. Each one of those colorectal crypts is whole

1331
01:20:21.700 --> 01:20:25.020
genome sequenced, and then they're put on a phylogenetic tree.

1332
01:20:25.580 --> 01:20:29.480
And again, based on that phylogenetic tree, one can time when this signature

1333
01:20:29.520 --> 01:20:33.160
occur. And this is very similar to how one times species

1334
01:20:33.200 --> 01:20:36.410
evolutions or how one times bacteria or viruses emergence

1335
01:20:37.219 --> 01:20:40.120
by using these phylogenetic trees and some markers of time.

1336
01:20:40.720 --> 01:20:44.340
And again, you can see here these are two colorectal crypts that have been

1337
01:20:44.400 --> 01:20:48.350
sequenced. They have a shared trunk, and that means they had

1338
01:20:48.350 --> 01:20:52.180
a shared ancestor. And that shared ancestor, as you can see,

1339
01:20:52.220 --> 01:20:56.040
the pink color here is the colibactin mutational signature, and that means

1340
01:20:56.100 --> 01:20:59.580
all the colibactin exposure happened in the shared ancestor.

1341
01:21:00.040 --> 01:21:04.000
And because we do not see any of the pink in the leaves, that

1342
01:21:04.080 --> 01:21:07.960
means this is something that happened in the ancestor, but it

1343
01:21:08.020 --> 01:21:11.990
didn't happen subsequently after the ancestor became these two

1344
01:21:12.060 --> 01:21:16.040
different colorectal crypts. So it's something that happens once or

1345
01:21:16.060 --> 01:21:18.400
it happens at one time point and then stops.

1346
01:21:18.900 --> 01:21:22.380
Now I'm showing you one phylogenetic tree. There is over 100 of those.

1347
01:21:22.400 --> 01:21:26.080
In almost every single case, you see this consistent result, something that

1348
01:21:26.120 --> 01:21:26.430
happens

1349
01:21:27.480 --> 01:21:30.780
at a single time point. Now, we can time that.

1350
01:21:30.820 --> 01:21:33.420
You can see there you have the clock-like mutational signatures.

1351
01:21:33.440 --> 01:21:35.080
We know how these signatures tick.

1352
01:21:35.560 --> 01:21:38.420
We can use their timing to say at what age does this happen.

1353
01:21:38.980 --> 01:21:42.600
And when we do this timing, you can say this is happening within the first five

1354
01:21:42.640 --> 01:21:46.600
years of life. So we're talking about an exposure that happens

1355
01:21:46.640 --> 01:21:48.059
in early childhood.

1356
01:21:49.400 --> 01:21:49.760
Excuse me.

1357
01:21:51.060 --> 01:21:53.800
Now, the question, okay, so we have an exposure.

1358
01:21:53.860 --> 01:21:57.720
That exposure happens early in life, early in tumor evolution, but does it

1359
01:21:57.760 --> 01:22:00.820
generate any driver mutations? Is it actually causative?

1360
01:22:01.240 --> 01:22:05.140
So then we looked at the APC driver, some of the first hit in the colorectal cancer

1361
01:22:05.180 --> 01:22:08.700
evolution, and we saw that in the colibactin cases, a substantial

1362
01:22:08.760 --> 01:22:12.240
proportion, more than 25%, were regenerated by the

1363
01:22:12.280 --> 01:22:13.900
colibactin mutational signature.

1364
01:22:14.260 --> 01:22:15.980
So not only did we have the

1365
01:22:16.020 --> 01:22:19.520
colibactin generating

1366
01:22:19.580 --> 01:22:23.240
mutational process, but generating some of the early driver mutations or some of

1367
01:22:23.280 --> 01:22:26.680
the first driver mutations in colorectal cancer evolution.

1368
01:22:27.680 --> 01:22:31.240
Now, what I'm going to do now, I'm going to summarize the talk, and I'm going to

1369
01:22:31.260 --> 01:22:35.040
tell you our hypothesis of what we think is causing some of the early onset

1370
01:22:35.140 --> 01:22:38.740
cases. So as part of the Mutographs Cancer Grand Challenge, we

1371
01:22:38.760 --> 01:22:41.990
profiled 1,000 colorectal cancers from 11 countries,

1372
01:22:43.060 --> 01:22:46.900
including 102 early onset cases. Again, you see all the

1373
01:22:46.940 --> 01:22:50.340
molecular subtypes that you expect for colorectal cancer.

1374
01:22:50.420 --> 01:22:54.160
There are over 47 different mutational signatures, most of them with

1375
01:22:54.200 --> 01:22:57.980
unknown etiologies. We are really looking forward to figuring out what causes these

1376
01:22:58.020 --> 01:23:01.130
signatures and whether we can explain cancer risk with them.

1377
01:23:01.860 --> 01:23:05.740
Multiple signatures are associated and highly enriched with early onset cases.

1378
01:23:06.480 --> 01:23:07.820
The one with colibactin

1379
01:23:08.800 --> 01:23:12.400
indicates that there has been a past colonization of pks+ positive

1380
01:23:12.460 --> 01:23:16.160
bacteria. And when you time that, you see it's happening early in the tumor

1381
01:23:16.200 --> 01:23:19.240
evolution, and it's happening very early in life.

1382
01:23:19.640 --> 01:23:23.600
But you don't only have a mutagenic exposure, you have a mutagenic exposure that's

1383
01:23:23.640 --> 01:23:27.080
generating some of the first driver mutations in colorectal cancer.

1384
01:23:28.280 --> 01:23:30.460
So based on that, we can construct a hypothesis

1385
01:23:31.480 --> 01:23:35.180
and our hypothesis is that early life exposure to the microbiome

1386
01:23:35.200 --> 01:23:38.860
carcinogens is actually causing at least some of the increase in early onset

1387
01:23:38.940 --> 01:23:42.520
cases. And it goes like this, you have a child, that child is

1388
01:23:42.640 --> 01:23:46.500
young, and it has colonization of this colibactin or other

1389
01:23:46.520 --> 01:23:48.740
mutagen producing bacteria. That

1390
01:23:51.380 --> 01:23:54.690
mutagenic bacteria generates many, many mutation in the colon tissue,

1391
01:23:55.340 --> 01:23:59.050
potentially some of the early drivers, and now you have a young child with many

1392
01:23:59.120 --> 01:24:02.420
mutations who is on the fast track for developing

1393
01:24:02.820 --> 01:24:04.120
cancer. Now,

1394
01:24:05.200 --> 01:24:08.500
this hypothesis has some support, and that support

1395
01:24:09.200 --> 01:24:12.859
comes specifically from looking at colorectal crypts in children.

1396
01:24:13.280 --> 01:24:17.080
All of the previous data I showed you, we were trying to time when the mutations

1397
01:24:17.120 --> 01:24:20.870
are happening. In this specific case, these are colon crypts from children that

1398
01:24:20.900 --> 01:24:23.200
have been whole genome sequenced.

1399
01:24:23.240 --> 01:24:25.300
And these are children from Europe, from the UK,

1400
01:24:26.500 --> 01:24:30.120
and there is about 80 of them. In 40% of these children, we

1401
01:24:30.200 --> 01:24:34.020
see colibactin exposure, and again, in majority of those children,

1402
01:24:34.100 --> 01:24:37.320
we see this colibactin exposure happening before the age of five.

1403
01:24:38.060 --> 01:24:40.940
But there is several different cases. You can see this child here.

1404
01:24:41.620 --> 01:24:45.460
This child has a small number of colibactin mutations, and it had

1405
01:24:45.480 --> 01:24:49.300
probably a very small exposure. And we wouldn't think that this specific

1406
01:24:49.310 --> 01:24:51.520
child would have high risk for developing cancer.

1407
01:24:51.580 --> 01:24:55.400
It has the clock-like signatures, but it doesn't have specifically a large number

1408
01:24:55.440 --> 01:24:59.340
of mutations. But there's other cases like this child here,

1409
01:24:59.440 --> 01:25:03.420
which I believe is either two or three years old, which has many, many thousands of

1410
01:25:03.440 --> 01:25:06.960
colibactin mutations being imprinted in colorectal epithelium.

1411
01:25:07.430 --> 01:25:10.560
And it has the mutational burden of some in their late 50s.

1412
01:25:11.040 --> 01:25:14.500
And if you have that many mutations at age two, well,

1413
01:25:14.600 --> 01:25:18.540
then our hypothesis would be that

1414
01:25:18.760 --> 01:25:22.320
these type of individuals will potentially have a higher risk for developing early

1415
01:25:22.360 --> 01:25:25.480
onset colorectal cancer later in life.

1416
01:25:26.840 --> 01:25:30.780
Now, I just want to try to say what we know for this hypothesis at the

1417
01:25:30.840 --> 01:25:34.780
moment. We know that the colibactin signatures are detected in about 40% of

1418
01:25:34.820 --> 01:25:37.400
normal colorectal crypts in children in the UK.

1419
01:25:37.880 --> 01:25:41.500
We suspect this will be very similar in the US and the rest of

1420
01:25:41.540 --> 01:25:45.220
Western Europe. We know that the colibactin signatures are very highly, three to

1421
01:25:45.260 --> 01:25:48.696
four times-fold enrich in early onset cases

1422
01:25:48.756 --> 01:25:52.526
versus late onset cases, and we do know for certainty that this

1423
01:25:52.556 --> 01:25:54.896
exposure happens before the age of five.

1424
01:25:54.956 --> 01:25:58.876
In fact, we think maybe it happens between the first nine to 18

1425
01:25:58.916 --> 01:26:01.996
months of life. So we're talking about a very, very early exposure.

1426
01:26:02.956 --> 01:26:06.556
The hypothesis, again, just to restate it here, is the colibactin is

1427
01:26:06.576 --> 01:26:10.346
generating these mutations, potentially generating these early driver mutations,

1428
01:26:10.416 --> 01:26:13.936
and again, putting you on a fast track for developing cancer because you have the

1429
01:26:13.996 --> 01:26:17.776
first hit, and then you can over age develop the second hit and the additional

1430
01:26:17.796 --> 01:26:21.416
clonal expansion. But you get cancer at age 20, 30,

1431
01:26:21.556 --> 01:26:23.476
40 instead of age 60, 70.

1432
01:26:24.856 --> 01:26:28.796
This is a hypothesis, and there is a lot of things that we need to prove to be able

1433
01:26:28.876 --> 01:26:30.616
to make sure that we understand it.

1434
01:26:31.136 --> 01:26:31.496
First,

1435
01:26:32.916 --> 01:26:36.696
we need to make sure that these signatures have been actually increasing with

1436
01:26:36.776 --> 01:26:40.436
the rates of early onset cancer. We don't know whether the

1437
01:26:40.456 --> 01:26:44.416
colibactin signatures have been increasing at the moment with the way early onset

1438
01:26:44.466 --> 01:26:47.956
cases have been increasing. So it is possible that this is an

1439
01:26:47.996 --> 01:26:51.776
exposure that has always existed, and that's the first time we capture it, or it's

1440
01:26:51.796 --> 01:26:54.556
possible that something has increased in recent years.

1441
01:26:55.376 --> 01:26:59.236
The second thing we need to do is we need to do a proper case control studies.

1442
01:26:59.516 --> 01:27:03.236
At the moment, we're comparing early onset cases to late onset cases.

1443
01:27:03.606 --> 01:27:06.276
What one needs to do and what we are planning to do is to compare

1444
01:27:07.936 --> 01:27:11.896
the normal colorectal tissues of early onset colorectal cancer carriers to age,

1445
01:27:12.036 --> 01:27:15.976
sex matched individuals that do not have early onset colorectal

1446
01:27:16.016 --> 01:27:19.936
cancer. And if this is causative, you're going to expect more mutations in the

1447
01:27:19.996 --> 01:27:23.916
cases versus the control. And the last and not least thing is trying

1448
01:27:23.976 --> 01:27:26.916
to think about intervention. How can we remove this exposure?

1449
01:27:27.016 --> 01:27:30.676
How we can modulate it, especially with something happening in early life?

1450
01:27:31.076 --> 01:27:34.916
And there is a number of ideas there, from symbiotic to different

1451
01:27:34.976 --> 01:27:38.616
types of intervention to make sure that children are not being

1452
01:27:38.676 --> 01:27:40.596
exposed to this mutagenic exposure.

1453
01:27:41.676 --> 01:27:42.816
Now, I should say that we have

1454
01:27:44.976 --> 01:27:48.596
summarized this hypothesis in a very nice cancer discovery piece.

1455
01:27:48.676 --> 01:27:52.216
It's one and a half pages. So if you're interested and if you

1456
01:27:52.596 --> 01:27:55.476
find that exciting, please, there is the QR code.

1457
01:27:56.315 --> 01:27:58.316
We have summarized what we know at the moment.

1458
01:27:58.376 --> 01:28:02.196
We have summarized ways to test this specific hypothesis and what we

1459
01:28:02.236 --> 01:28:05.376
didn't mean for the hypothesis to be true or to be false.

1460
01:28:06.076 --> 01:28:06.476
And again,

1461
01:28:07.296 --> 01:28:11.176
special thanks to Mike Stratton and Paul Brenner, who really have been my partners

1462
01:28:11.216 --> 01:28:14.896
in crime, and with whom we are really excited to investigate whether this

1463
01:28:14.976 --> 01:28:18.456
specific early life mutagenesis is causing the early onset

1464
01:28:18.516 --> 01:28:22.476
colorectal cancer. But again, I want to emphasize, even if it isn't causing early

1465
01:28:22.516 --> 01:28:26.236
onset colorectal cancer, we are seeing a mutagenic exposure in

1466
01:28:26.416 --> 01:28:29.976
40% of young children, and this is something that's,

1467
01:28:31.376 --> 01:28:34.036
well, to put it mildly, not a good thing to be happening.

1468
01:28:34.116 --> 01:28:38.076
So one way or another, we need to figure out how we can stop this

1469
01:28:38.176 --> 01:28:41.936
early exposure, because we do not want a child at the age of two to have the

1470
01:28:41.956 --> 01:28:44.376
mutational burden of a 65-year-old.

1471
01:28:45.556 --> 01:28:47.516
With that, I want to just do brief acknowledgments.

1472
01:28:47.576 --> 01:28:50.856
The Mutographs team is very large with many people.

