this model, indicating that the liver

1716
01:43:42.900 --> 01:43:46.310
environment is distinctly different and fosters

1717
01:43:46.320 --> 01:43:49.080
establishment of metastasis in the postpartum period.

1718
01:43:50.620 --> 01:43:54.000
So what is this link between the mammary gland and the liver?

1719
01:43:54.020 --> 01:43:54.270
Well, this

1720
01:43:56.100 --> 01:43:58.610
biology has been a lot of fun to decipher.

1721
01:43:59.170 --> 01:44:02.460
So what we've learned is that as the mammary gland expands and

1722
01:44:02.500 --> 01:44:06.280
matures to be able to make milk and secrete it, the

1723
01:44:06.340 --> 01:44:10.020
liver also expands and increases metabolic output

1724
01:44:10.320 --> 01:44:14.260
and is the major source of the resources that are needed to

1725
01:44:14.320 --> 01:44:18.240
make milk. And so they're directly linked during lactation

1726
01:44:18.620 --> 01:44:22.480
to support the incredibly metabolic demanding process of

1727
01:44:22.620 --> 01:44:25.960
lactation. And surprisingly, we discovered,

1728
01:44:26.440 --> 01:44:29.660
mostly in rodent models, that upon weaning,

1729
01:44:30.380 --> 01:44:34.340
the liver also undergoes a weaning-induced liver

1730
01:44:34.380 --> 01:44:35.050
involution. And

1731
01:44:36.280 --> 01:44:38.380
most of this data is again published.

1732
01:44:38.500 --> 01:44:42.320
We have human correlative data that indicate that this is an

1733
01:44:42.440 --> 01:44:45.580
aspect of a normal, healthy pregnancy as well.

1734
01:44:45.590 --> 01:44:49.260
But I think the most compelling way to show this biology is with recent

1735
01:44:49.360 --> 01:44:51.840
RNA seq data that was published last

1736
01:44:52.560 --> 01:44:56.530
year by graduate student Michelle Ozaki, who has since gone on

1737
01:44:56.560 --> 01:45:00.385
to postdoc training.And what we find is that at the molecular

1738
01:45:00.476 --> 01:45:04.446
level, the liver mirrors the mammary gland with respect to

1739
01:45:04.616 --> 01:45:08.596
the transition between nulliparous and lactation and

1740
01:45:08.636 --> 01:45:11.016
the transition from lactation to weaning.

1741
01:45:11.286 --> 01:45:14.576
And so here you see individual animals from nulliparous

1742
01:45:14.656 --> 01:45:16.676
lactation, two, four, six, eight, and

1743
01:45:17.516 --> 01:45:21.196
eight days post-wean, and then regressed, which means that the mammary gland is

1744
01:45:21.256 --> 01:45:24.686
fully regressed and is no longer undergoing weaning-induced

1745
01:45:24.716 --> 01:45:28.496
involution. And if you look at cell cycle proliferation genes, you can

1746
01:45:28.536 --> 01:45:32.336
see in the liver, the normal liver, that's a hotspot for

1747
01:45:32.596 --> 01:45:36.576
proliferation during lactation, indicating the metabolic demand that the

1748
01:45:36.616 --> 01:45:40.276
liver is on and the need for additional hepatocytes to meet that demand.

1749
01:45:40.696 --> 01:45:44.556
You see, during lactation, this upregulation of anabolic

1750
01:45:44.636 --> 01:45:46.576
metabolism, including

1751
01:45:47.476 --> 01:45:50.076
materials that the mammary gland needs to make milk.

1752
01:45:50.376 --> 01:45:54.076
But as early as two days post-wean, there's a shift to catabolic

1753
01:45:54.136 --> 01:45:57.636
metabolism as these substrates build up, but there's no longer

1754
01:45:58.016 --> 01:46:01.936
suckling. There is a mechanism to reabsorb those into the

1755
01:46:01.976 --> 01:46:05.896
liver. This mechanism of resorption is actually directly

1756
01:46:05.956 --> 01:46:09.916
linked to the induction of hepatocyte cell death in

1757
01:46:09.976 --> 01:46:13.936
work that we've published. And this cell death is associated, again,

1758
01:46:13.976 --> 01:46:17.376
with fibroblast activation and this pretty intense

1759
01:46:17.476 --> 01:46:19.076
immune change in the

1760
01:46:19.876 --> 01:46:20.836
normal liver.

1761
01:46:22.976 --> 01:46:26.336
Michelle also looked for whether there was evidence for

1762
01:46:27.016 --> 01:46:30.716
involution-educated metastatic niche occurring, and she

1763
01:46:30.816 --> 01:46:34.516
used two publicly available data sets from

1764
01:46:34.656 --> 01:46:38.636
tumor-educated metastatic niches in the liver from PDAC and

1765
01:46:38.656 --> 01:46:41.736
gastric cancer and found that those

1766
01:46:41.776 --> 01:46:45.756
tumor-educated metastatic niches were both upregulated in our

1767
01:46:45.836 --> 01:46:49.656
normal liver. And so our model is that during weaning-induced

1768
01:46:50.156 --> 01:46:53.816
involution, the liver has a myriad of changes that

1769
01:46:53.896 --> 01:46:57.736
create a pre-metastatic niche in the absence

1770
01:46:57.836 --> 01:46:58.436
of a tumor.

1771
01:46:59.876 --> 01:47:03.756
But for the unfortunate group of young women who may have a tumor,

1772
01:47:04.356 --> 01:47:08.116
it makes a perfect site for metastasis and could

1773
01:47:08.126 --> 01:47:12.076
explain the increased risk of liver metastasis that's specifically

1774
01:47:12.116 --> 01:47:15.336
observed in postpartum patients.

1775
01:47:15.676 --> 01:47:16.646
Michelle went on in

1776
01:47:17.856 --> 01:47:21.056
work that's currently unpublished to try to understand what's the role of the

1777
01:47:21.156 --> 01:47:25.016
normal liver fibroblast in weaning to

1778
01:47:25.076 --> 01:47:28.956
establishing this metastatic niche, because it's known that cancer-associated

1779
01:47:29.036 --> 01:47:32.896
fibroblasts are very important in establishing the liver metastatic

1780
01:47:32.956 --> 01:47:34.116
niche in other

1781
01:47:35.476 --> 01:47:38.946
models. And so she developed a live infusion

1782
01:47:39.036 --> 01:47:42.516
protocol where we could enrich for the hepatic stellate cells, which are the liver

1783
01:47:42.536 --> 01:47:46.516
fibroblasts. And by a simple PCR analysis, you can see that this

1784
01:47:46.556 --> 01:47:50.036
enriched population expresses high levels of a canonical

1785
01:47:50.116 --> 01:47:53.696
fibroblast marker, PDGFRA alpha, but does not express

1786
01:47:54.136 --> 01:47:57.756
increased levels of CD45 immune marker, CD31

1787
01:47:57.796 --> 01:48:01.296
endothelial cell marker, or a marker for hepatocytes.

1788
01:48:01.836 --> 01:48:02.176
She then

1789
01:48:03.596 --> 01:48:06.906
isolated these liver fibroblasts from either

1790
01:48:08.036 --> 01:48:11.696
donor nulliparous mice livers or from mice that had

1791
01:48:11.756 --> 01:48:14.756
recently weaned, so involution day four livers,

1792
01:48:15.576 --> 01:48:19.316
combined those fibroblasts with tumor cells,

1793
01:48:20.116 --> 01:48:23.596
and then used a flank model and then asked, was there any difference in the ability

1794
01:48:23.636 --> 01:48:27.336
of these normal liver fibroblasts to differentially

1795
01:48:27.656 --> 01:48:31.366
impact tumor development? And you can see here that the tumors

1796
01:48:31.456 --> 01:48:35.216
grew more robustly in the involution group compared to the nulliparous

1797
01:48:35.296 --> 01:48:39.176
group, and this is data showing this increased tumor volume in

1798
01:48:39.236 --> 01:48:39.896
two different

1799
01:48:40.816 --> 01:48:41.376
models.

1800
01:48:46.196 --> 01:48:50.126
By performing single-cell RNAseq on this isolated population,

1801
01:48:50.196 --> 01:48:54.036
it was quite clear that the involution day four

1802
01:48:54.456 --> 01:48:58.256
fibroblasts are really molecularly quite distinct from the nulliparous and

1803
01:48:58.296 --> 01:49:00.966
distinct from the involution, which are shown here in blue.

1804
01:49:01.676 --> 01:49:04.736
And by using publicly available data sets,

1805
01:49:05.416 --> 01:49:08.836
Michelle was able to show that these nulliparous fibroblasts were

1806
01:49:08.856 --> 01:49:11.916
particularly enriched in previously published

1807
01:49:12.276 --> 01:49:14.356
cancer-associated fibroblasts

1808
01:49:15.256 --> 01:49:18.996
data sets from breast with fibroblasts that express high

1809
01:49:19.116 --> 01:49:23.076
levels of extracellular matrix proteins, from pancreatic cancer that express

1810
01:49:23.116 --> 01:49:27.046
high levels of extracellular matrix proteins in their activated state, and

1811
01:49:27.056 --> 01:49:30.576
from cancer-associated fibroblasts in breast that have immune

1812
01:49:30.756 --> 01:49:32.136
modulatory activity.

1813
01:49:33.066 --> 01:49:36.736
And consistent with these phenotypes, when she stained

1814
01:49:36.916 --> 01:49:38.476
these tumors for

1815
01:49:39.836 --> 01:49:41.236
matrix, here we're showing

1816
01:49:42.656 --> 01:49:45.616
collagen III, collagen I, and fibronectin.

1817
01:49:45.696 --> 01:49:49.646
You can see that the involution group tumors are more stromalized, and this

1818
01:49:49.676 --> 01:49:53.436
can be quantitated. And by multiplex IHC looking at the

1819
01:49:53.456 --> 01:49:56.926
immune milieu of these tumors, we can find that

1820
01:49:56.956 --> 01:50:00.656
the involution group tumors have an increase in tumor

1821
01:50:00.756 --> 01:50:04.656
cells that are known as myeloid-derived suppressor cells, and this is in

1822
01:50:04.696 --> 01:50:05.556
phenotype only.

1823
01:50:06.636 --> 01:50:10.476
And you can see this increase in the level of these cells in

1824
01:50:10.536 --> 01:50:12.536
involution tumors compared to nulliparous.

1825
01:50:12.976 --> 01:50:16.716
And then when you look at for the activated CD8

1826
01:50:16.776 --> 01:50:19.956
T cells that would be responsible for clearing these tumors, you can see a

1827
01:50:19.996 --> 01:50:23.656
suppression of that population. And this ratio is known to be very

1828
01:50:23.696 --> 01:50:26.606
important in regulating immune surveillance.

1829
01:50:27.936 --> 01:50:29.376
So with these studies,

1830
01:50:30.196 --> 01:50:31.576
we kind of felt like we had

1831
01:50:32.516 --> 01:50:35.986
shown clearly that postpartum breast cancer cases are at increased

1832
01:50:36.056 --> 01:50:38.086
risk for liver metastasis.

1833
01:50:38.996 --> 01:50:42.856
And we showed that weaning-induced involution is a very

1834
01:50:42.916 --> 01:50:46.176
likely mechanism to account for this increased risk.

1835
01:50:46.566 --> 01:50:49.716
And so we next wanted to ask, what could we learn by

1836
01:50:51.096 --> 01:50:54.496
looking at actual tumors, breast cancer liver metastasis

1837
01:50:54.536 --> 01:50:58.476
tumors in the metastatic site? And so this is work

1838
01:50:59.476 --> 01:51:03.376
done by Dr. Hatun Duran Cich in my group, who had a

1839
01:51:03.816 --> 01:51:06.356
poster a couple of days ago, and I hope some of you got to see it.

1840
01:51:06.856 --> 01:51:10.480
And the data-I'm going to show both of these data

1841
01:51:10.820 --> 01:51:12.220
combined because they're replicates.

1842
01:51:12.260 --> 01:51:15.220
Some people like graphs, some people like circles.

1843
01:51:15.680 --> 01:51:19.380
And what we found in our cohort-- So first of all, there's 47 women that were

1844
01:51:19.400 --> 01:51:23.380
enrolled in this study, and there was no selection criteria for these women.

1845
01:51:23.440 --> 01:51:26.760
We didn't look for young women. We didn't look for PARUS women, postpartum women.

1846
01:51:27.090 --> 01:51:30.800
We just took all comers with two criteria, that they would sign

1847
01:51:30.840 --> 01:51:33.980
informed consent and that they were not at any increased risk

1848
01:51:34.760 --> 01:51:38.680
by donating a research-only biopsy for our studies.

1849
01:51:39.460 --> 01:51:42.700
And what we found in this small cohort was that we

1850
01:51:43.380 --> 01:51:46.940
were already enriched in young women and postpartum breast cancer cases

1851
01:51:47.080 --> 01:51:50.580
compared to the national

1852
01:51:50.740 --> 01:51:54.480
average of young onset breast cancer and postpartum breast

1853
01:51:54.560 --> 01:51:54.960
cancer.

1854
01:51:56.280 --> 01:52:00.000
So one potential bias is that we could have an institution that sees an

1855
01:52:00.040 --> 01:52:03.949
exceptionally large number of young onset breast cancer patients, and that

1856
01:52:03.980 --> 01:52:07.880
is not the case. We find that the patient population at OHSU

1857
01:52:07.960 --> 01:52:11.760
reflects the national average. And so while this is a very small

1858
01:52:11.940 --> 01:52:15.580
study, it's pretty remarkable that already we're seeing this high enrichment in

1859
01:52:15.620 --> 01:52:18.700
young cases and high enrichment in postpartum cases.

1860
01:52:20.920 --> 01:52:24.860
Hatun went on to ask the question, what

1861
01:52:24.880 --> 01:52:28.080
were the primary cancers that these women were diagnosed with?

1862
01:52:28.130 --> 01:52:28.920
And this was pretty

1863
01:52:30.580 --> 01:52:34.300
eye-opening data for me. The vast majority of these women were

1864
01:52:34.340 --> 01:52:38.140
diagnosed with luminal A, the most indolent form of breast

1865
01:52:38.220 --> 01:52:40.120
cancer, and combined,

1866
01:52:42.260 --> 01:52:44.280
luminal cancers were the dominant by far.

1867
01:52:46.100 --> 01:52:49.920
50% of them were low grade, and 50% of them were low

1868
01:52:50.020 --> 01:52:53.180
stage. So these would be normally considered an indolent

1869
01:52:53.240 --> 01:52:56.960
cancer with low probability of metastasis, yet

1870
01:52:57.020 --> 01:52:59.780
here we have these cancers residing in the

1871
01:52:59.820 --> 01:53:03.640
liver. Hatun then went on to look

1872
01:53:03.700 --> 01:53:07.600
at what is the fate of these tumors in the liver themselves, and these dots

1873
01:53:07.640 --> 01:53:11.460
represent that these tumors retained their ER positivity at a high

1874
01:53:11.520 --> 01:53:15.340
level. And GATA-3 is a marker for luminal origin,

1875
01:53:15.440 --> 01:53:19.339
and you can see they're largely ER positive and luminal in origin.

1876
01:53:19.740 --> 01:53:23.560
The red dots represent ER positive cases that were positive

1877
01:53:23.720 --> 01:53:27.540
in the primary tumor but lost ER in the secondary site

1878
01:53:27.780 --> 01:53:31.700
in the liver, and you can see that they largely retained that luminal

1879
01:53:31.720 --> 01:53:35.340
phenotype. And these blue dots are the very few cases that we got

1880
01:53:35.640 --> 01:53:39.050
with taking all comers that were ER negative to begin with and

1881
01:53:39.140 --> 01:53:42.260
retained ER negativity in the

1882
01:53:43.600 --> 01:53:44.740
liver metastatic site.

1883
01:53:46.500 --> 01:53:47.490
So the question was,

1884
01:53:48.840 --> 01:53:52.660
how could these relatively indolent tumor cells that we think of

1885
01:53:52.720 --> 01:53:54.820
as having really low metastatic potential

1886
01:53:55.740 --> 01:53:59.660
be thriving so in the liver? And so we're only scratching the surface

1887
01:53:59.720 --> 01:54:02.849
on this, but I think it's a really important future direction.

1888
01:54:02.880 --> 01:54:06.600
To ask this question, we focused on cases where we had adjacent

1889
01:54:06.680 --> 01:54:07.050
normal

1890
01:54:08.840 --> 01:54:12.560
to the tumor. The normal is stained with HepPar, and

1891
01:54:12.600 --> 01:54:16.380
because these tumors are almost exclusively luminal, we stain the tumor for

1892
01:54:16.400 --> 01:54:20.220
GATA-3. And what we found was that the

1893
01:54:20.240 --> 01:54:24.080
vast majority of the way that these tumor cells

1894
01:54:24.120 --> 01:54:27.840
are interacting with the liver is through something called replacement growth,

1895
01:54:27.860 --> 01:54:31.720
which was originally defined in colon cancer metastasizing to the liver.

1896
01:54:32.080 --> 01:54:36.000
And the simplest way to describe it is the hepatocytes

1897
01:54:36.040 --> 01:54:38.680
are simply replaced with tumor cells.

1898
01:54:39.830 --> 01:54:43.780
So there's not a massive tumor that forms, but rather the tumor

1899
01:54:43.840 --> 01:54:47.240
seems to use the existing architecture of the liver to

1900
01:54:47.280 --> 01:54:50.520
establish itself, and this was a pretty dominant pathway.

1901
01:54:50.960 --> 01:54:54.600
And I think the most compelling way to show that we think that

1902
01:54:54.780 --> 01:54:56.460
many of these tumors really are

1903
01:54:57.580 --> 01:55:01.220
co-opting the existing liver with very little changes

1904
01:55:01.880 --> 01:55:05.520
to their own biology is shown in this image here, which on the left again

1905
01:55:05.560 --> 01:55:07.510
shows a HepPar positive

1906
01:55:08.700 --> 01:55:12.120
normal liver, the green tumor

1907
01:55:12.340 --> 01:55:15.909
cells. And here is stained for validated

1908
01:55:16.320 --> 01:55:18.530
liver sinusoidal markers.

1909
01:55:19.440 --> 01:55:23.350
I think you're hard pressed if we drew a line in here to say that

1910
01:55:23.380 --> 01:55:27.080
this is clearly tumor vasculature and this is clearly normal

1911
01:55:27.100 --> 01:55:30.580
vasculature. These tumor cells do not seem to need

1912
01:55:32.420 --> 01:55:35.080
the ability to induce new angiogenesis

1913
01:55:35.200 --> 01:55:39.040
desmoplasia. They seem to just readily

1914
01:55:39.080 --> 01:55:42.950
interact with the existing liver, which I think is going to be both a challenge and

1915
01:55:43.000 --> 01:55:44.000
hopefully a promise.

1916
01:55:44.900 --> 01:55:45.650
So in summary,

1917
01:55:46.700 --> 01:55:50.340
ER positive young onset breast cancer is increasing, and I think it's

1918
01:55:50.380 --> 01:55:54.320
important that we continue to study reproductive risk factors,

1919
01:55:54.420 --> 01:55:57.920
but I think it's probably more important at this point in

1920
01:55:57.980 --> 01:56:01.340
time to study lifetime exposures

1921
01:56:01.520 --> 01:56:04.940
and the massive changes in dietary

1922
01:56:04.980 --> 01:56:08.880
patterns and exercise and physical activity

1923
01:56:08.940 --> 01:56:10.760
that have occurred over the last 90 years.

1924
01:56:11.520 --> 01:56:14.880
I want to remind you that 75% of all young onset breast cancer

1925
01:56:15.060 --> 01:56:17.700
lethality actually occurs in ER positive cases,

1926
01:56:18.700 --> 01:56:21.080
with the highest mortality in postpartum breast cancer.

1927
01:56:21.520 --> 01:56:25.210
That doesn't say that we don't need to understand ER-negative disease because

1928
01:56:25.280 --> 01:56:27.700
it metastasizes much quicker.

1929
01:56:28.840 --> 01:56:32.700
The length of life is truly shortened in young onset breast cancer

1930
01:56:32.740 --> 01:56:36.380
cases with postpartum breast cancer with ER-negative disease.

1931
01:56:38.140 --> 01:56:41.980
That even patients with really classically really good prognostic

1932
01:56:42.080 --> 01:56:45.960
cancers, when diagnosed postpartum, are at risk

1933
01:56:45.980 --> 01:56:49.490
for liver metastasis. And this is really an opportunity for increased

1934
01:56:49.580 --> 01:56:53.480
surveillance, monitoring, and I would argue

1935
01:56:53.540 --> 01:56:56.630
increased treatment escalation.

1936
01:56:57.140 --> 01:57:00.660
That they're not indolent. They should be treated as high-risk

1937
01:57:00.740 --> 01:57:04.560
patients. And we believe that weaning-induced liver involution is the

1938
01:57:04.580 --> 01:57:08.480
likely mechanism. And so in sum, studying postpartum biology,

1939
01:57:08.620 --> 01:57:12.220
I think, represents a really unique opportunity for early

1940
01:57:12.280 --> 01:57:16.020
detection prevention, which I haven't really covered, which is a part of my

1941
01:57:16.900 --> 01:57:20.728
motivation, and treatment strategies.So clearly,

1942
01:57:21.308 --> 01:57:25.018
it takes a village to do this

1943
01:57:25.068 --> 01:57:29.008
work, and I want to highlight Hatun, Jackie,

1944
01:57:29.088 --> 01:57:33.048
and Michelle, current and recent past member of

1945
