01:58:24.468 --> 01:58:24.868
studies.

1960
01:58:25.758 --> 01:58:26.708
So, thank you very much.

1961
01:58:30.608 --> 01:58:35.488
Thank

1962
01:58:35.528 --> 01:58:38.658
you, Dr Shadeen. So I just have a few summaries,

1963
01:58:39.148 --> 01:58:40.988
slides to close out the session.

1964
01:58:42.368 --> 01:58:46.348
So a few take home messages, I think from today's talks, we've learned that cancer

1965
01:58:46.408 --> 01:58:49.808
incidence is rising in young adults across several different tumor types.

1966
01:58:50.608 --> 01:58:54.448
The trends are better visualized through a birth cohort lens rather than

1967
01:58:54.528 --> 01:58:58.508
age. Future disparities are already starting to emerge based on these

1968
01:58:58.568 --> 01:59:02.228
trends. And also trends in young adults are really potentially

1969
01:59:02.268 --> 01:59:05.068
early signals of broader trends in the population.

1970
01:59:06.408 --> 01:59:09.928
Colorectal cancer is an example of convergent pathways of

1971
01:59:09.968 --> 01:59:13.668
metabolic disease, microbiome, epigenetics across a life

1972
01:59:13.728 --> 01:59:16.108
course as cancer drivers in young adults.

1973
01:59:17.008 --> 01:59:20.608
Mutational profiling of tumors really point to early life factors

1974
01:59:20.988 --> 01:59:24.448
and exposures, and potentially things like cholabactin-producing

1975
01:59:24.468 --> 01:59:27.418
bacteria as a risk factor for early onset colorectal cancer.

1976
01:59:28.428 --> 01:59:32.408
And then early onset breast cancer has been hypothesized to maybe be associated

1977
01:59:32.428 --> 01:59:36.268
with changes in hormone exposure, although the epidemiological data is not quite

1978
01:59:36.308 --> 01:59:39.618
there, but is certainly associated with worsened outcomes, and

1979
01:59:39.648 --> 01:59:43.618
postpartum breast cancer may provide us some window into understanding that

1980
01:59:43.628 --> 01:59:44.068
disease.

1981
01:59:45.668 --> 01:59:48.888
So what are some future challenges and opportunities for the field of early onset

1982
01:59:48.968 --> 01:59:52.848
cancer? I think we need to do our best to leverage our knowledge

1983
01:59:52.888 --> 01:59:56.748
of existing risk factors. I think we have to do our best to identify new

1984
01:59:56.788 --> 02:00:00.328
risk factors through life course epidemiology cohorts,

1985
02:00:00.868 --> 02:00:04.608
novel approaches to biospecimen profiling to infer exposures

1986
02:00:04.748 --> 02:00:08.638
and also their biological effects, and develop methods to really

1987
02:00:08.768 --> 02:00:11.188
